WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:03.860
- The following is a conversation
with Rick Beato, legendary

00:00:03.940 --> 00:00:07.800
music educator, interviewer,
producer, songwriter, and a true

00:00:07.820 --> 00:00:14.640
multi-instrument musician, playing guitar,
bass, cello, and piano. Rick, with his

00:00:14.700 --> 00:00:18.430
incredible YouTube channel,
celebrates great musicians and

00:00:18.680 --> 00:00:22.560
musical ideas, and helps
millions of people, including

00:00:22.620 --> 00:00:26.300
me, fall in love with great music all over

00:00:26.380 --> 00:00:30.260
again. This is the Lex
Fridman Podcast. To support

00:00:30.320 --> 00:00:33.940
it, please check out our sponsors
in the description, where you can

00:00:34.020 --> 00:00:37.820
also find links to contact
me, ask questions, give

00:00:37.900 --> 00:00:45.780
feedback, and so on. And now, dear
friends, here's Rick Beato. You had, I

00:00:45.800 --> 00:00:48.970
think, an incredibly fun and
diverse beginning to your music

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:52.960
journey. I heard somewhere that one of
the things that made you fall in love

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:57.080
with music was listening to guitar
solos, some epic guitar solos.

00:00:57.900 --> 00:01:03.220
What's an early guitar solo that you
remember you connected to spiritually,

00:01:04.180 --> 00:01:07.800
musically, where you're like,
"Wow, there's magic in this"?

00:01:07.820 --> 00:01:11.720
- Well, the first solo that I learned
was "Hey Joe." It was actually a good

00:01:11.840 --> 00:01:14.860
beginner song, you know, when
I first started playing the

00:01:14.900 --> 00:01:22.470
guitar, because it has pretty simple
chords, right? So it's like E, C, G, D, A.

00:01:22.540 --> 00:01:26.530
And I learned the solo, and I figured
out this, like, I'll say it's this

00:01:26.560 --> 00:01:30.360
pentatonic scale, E minor pentatonic scale though.
I didn't know that's what it was called, but

00:01:30.400 --> 00:01:34.280
learned this thing, and it's like,
"Whoa, he's just in this one shape

00:01:34.300 --> 00:01:37.780
here." Now, there was no... You
couldn't go look anything up. You

00:01:37.860 --> 00:01:41.740
just, if you could figure out the notes,
you noticed that there was a little pattern

00:01:41.750 --> 00:01:46.820
to it. And then I got so
obsessed with it, and I showed

00:01:46.840 --> 00:01:50.270
my younger brother John, who started playing
guitar right at the same time I did.

00:01:50.300 --> 00:01:54.040
So I was 14, he was 11. And I

00:01:54.100 --> 00:01:57.910
would play rhythm for him for five
minutes while he would solo over

00:01:57.920 --> 00:02:01.420
Hey Joe. And then as soon as I'd start soloing,
he'd throw the guitar down, then we'd get in a

00:02:01.560 --> 00:02:06.900
fight. And so my mom eventually was
like, "What is going on here?" And I was

00:02:06.960 --> 00:02:09.829
like, "John won't play rhythm."

00:02:11.200 --> 00:02:14.960
"John won't play rhythm for me." She's
like, "Okay, I'll play rhythm for you.

00:02:14.980 --> 00:02:17.240
What, what are the chords?" And—

00:02:17.340 --> 00:02:17.430
- That's awesome.

00:02:17.430 --> 00:02:20.690
- ... I was like, "Okay,
it's like E, C, G, D, A."

00:02:20.690 --> 00:02:25.600
And so my mom would literally play
rhythm for 20 minutes while I'd play.

00:02:25.620 --> 00:02:27.100
- Hashtag parenting.

00:02:27.140 --> 00:02:31.120
- That's amazing. When I look back on
it now, my mom's been gone for 10

00:02:31.160 --> 00:02:35.440
years now. When I look back on it, it's
like, "My God, my parents were so cool."

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:39.640
- We should mention that "Hey Joe," and
Hendrix in general, is kind of known

00:02:39.800 --> 00:02:43.690
for the rhythm not being simple rhythm,
just the chords that you mentioned.

00:02:43.700 --> 00:02:47.670
It's what you do with those chords. It's
almost improvisation, the rhythm side.

00:02:47.680 --> 00:02:51.590
- He did all those really cool chord
fragments, riffs, and things like that,

00:02:51.640 --> 00:02:54.620
that's just part of his...
That's the Hendrix style.

00:02:54.640 --> 00:02:58.590
- What do you think? I mean, many people put
Hendrix as the greatest guitarist of all time.

00:02:58.600 --> 00:03:00.240
What do you think is part of that?

00:03:00.300 --> 00:03:02.280
- You know, I make lists.

00:03:02.340 --> 00:03:05.900
- You do. If you somehow don't
know who Rick Beato is,

00:03:06.040 --> 00:03:10.000
go on YouTube right now
and watch your excellent

00:03:10.060 --> 00:03:15.100
interviews with musicians, watch your
breakdown analysis of different songs,

00:03:16.080 --> 00:03:19.860
and watch your top 20 lists, where you're

00:03:19.880 --> 00:03:23.700
very opinionated, sometimes very
openly critical about certain

00:03:23.720 --> 00:03:26.020
kinds of songs. It's
fun. Opinions are fun.

00:03:27.340 --> 00:03:30.060
- But they do change, Lex, from day to day.

00:03:30.080 --> 00:03:31.280
- Yeah, exactly.

00:03:31.290 --> 00:03:35.080
- You know, like I... But when, anytime
I do a list, if I do 20, I like to do

00:03:35.280 --> 00:03:38.920
20 because that gives me some leeway
to throw in. I have to throw in

00:03:39.020 --> 00:03:42.040
something that is so
weird that people, you

00:03:42.100 --> 00:03:46.010
know... So, something that
a lot of people won't know,

00:03:46.080 --> 00:03:49.910
just to have it on there, so I can
at least introduce a per- you know,

00:03:49.960 --> 00:03:53.580
I'll put somebody like a- Allan
Holdsworth, who's a famous fusion guitar

00:03:53.600 --> 00:03:57.370
player. I'll throw in one of his
solos or something. Just some, some

00:03:57.440 --> 00:04:01.350
oddball solo in there, just so that people,
as they're listening down the list, will get

00:04:01.380 --> 00:04:05.250
exposed to something they would
not necessarily get exposed to.

00:04:05.280 --> 00:04:10.700
- Yeah, a lot of variety. But Hendrix...
Did you show up here today, Rick,

00:04:12.480 --> 00:04:16.560
try to tell me that Hendrix is not up there?
I just am getting that vibe right now.

00:04:16.600 --> 00:04:19.780
- No, I'm not. I, but I don't
want to say greatest, you

00:04:19.820 --> 00:04:26.500
know... You, you can say, well, there, there
are people that inspired Jimi Hendrix.

00:04:26.540 --> 00:04:30.420
Charlie Christian, older guitar players.
Charlie Christian, Django Reinhardt

00:04:30.460 --> 00:04:34.120
were the first two really
big, and probably, and Andrés

00:04:34.200 --> 00:04:38.020
Segovia were, were three
of the giants of the

00:04:38.180 --> 00:04:41.900
20th century, as far as guitar
influences for most of the

00:04:41.920 --> 00:04:43.440
players that were to follow.

00:04:43.500 --> 00:04:47.380
- So here, going to Perplexity, Django
Reinhardt was, of course, a jazz guitarist

00:04:47.400 --> 00:04:50.820
and composer, active mainly in France,
and is widely regarded as one of the

00:04:50.880 --> 00:04:54.700
greatest guitarists in jazz history.

00:04:54.760 --> 00:04:58.539
- So, Django was... Well,
there's a huge movement

00:04:58.620 --> 00:05:01.969
right now, Gypsy Jazz
Movement, as they call it-

00:05:01.969 --> 00:05:05.560
... that is kind of built
around this style of

00:05:05.640 --> 00:05:09.490
music that he played back in the
early 20th century. One of the things

00:05:09.560 --> 00:05:12.800
about Django is that he was in a fire,

00:05:13.980 --> 00:05:17.960
and he had two of his third
and fourth finger, so

00:05:17.980 --> 00:05:21.940
his ring finger and pinky were
essentially melted together. He had

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:25.930
no use of them. Although he could use
them while he was chording, but a lot of

00:05:25.960 --> 00:05:34.800
these incredibly fast lines, he's just
playing with two fingers. And it's amazing.

00:05:44.580 --> 00:05:48.860
- That... What is that?
So that's Gypsy Jazz.

00:05:48.880 --> 00:05:51.760
- That's Gypsy Jazz, yeah.

00:05:53.640 --> 00:05:57.880
Him, Stéphane Grappelli was a
violinist that played with him a lot.

00:05:58.600 --> 00:06:01.000
- How much of this is improvisation?

00:06:01.060 --> 00:06:03.260
- Everything he's doing there is improvised.

00:06:07.708 --> 00:06:14.658
- It feels so free. And fun like
swing, and then at least you said

00:06:15.348 --> 00:06:19.328
pre-bebop. So bebop was a kind of
jazz that was also influential

00:06:19.388 --> 00:06:23.148
on you in your own life
journey. And it's this

00:06:23.508 --> 00:06:27.238
complicated, legendary kind of jazz that
was very influential on the music that

00:06:27.328 --> 00:06:29.008
followed. So what was bebop?

00:06:29.028 --> 00:06:32.858
- Well, after the big
bands were happening in

00:06:32.888 --> 00:06:35.828
the, you know, from the
'20s through the '40s,

00:06:37.708 --> 00:06:41.568
Small, people would go out and
play in small groups that they

00:06:41.608 --> 00:06:45.428
would tour with. And Charlie Parker,
who's really kind of the, one of the

00:06:45.488 --> 00:06:49.428
main figures of early bebop,
really developed the language of

00:06:49.468 --> 00:06:54.058
it. Usually, the music that they're playing
over are standard chord progressions-

00:06:54.168 --> 00:06:57.488
... that they would use
as vehicles to improvise

00:06:57.568 --> 00:07:02.528
over. A lot of them were AA,
BA form. And Charlie Parker

00:07:03.828 --> 00:07:07.798
created this language
of improvisation that

00:07:07.808 --> 00:07:10.868
was far more sophisticated
than the swing players

00:07:11.988 --> 00:07:15.028
of the big band era. You know,
think of people like Benny

00:07:15.068 --> 00:07:19.008
Goodman of that era. They
would have really fast tempo

00:07:19.108 --> 00:07:24.748
songs, angular lines, chromaticism,
things like that, chromatic notes.

00:07:24.788 --> 00:07:27.008
- Chromatic notes are just
notes next to each other on-

00:07:27.048 --> 00:07:27.868
- Next to each other, yeah

00:07:27.908 --> 00:07:28.468
- ... on the keyboard.

00:07:28.528 --> 00:07:30.208
- I like to think of it as connecting notes.

00:07:30.248 --> 00:07:33.568
- Connecting. You're putting in more notes
than are supposed to be there and so

00:07:33.688 --> 00:07:35.818
doing, creating some interesting texture.

00:07:36.528 --> 00:07:39.238
- Yeah, so that is one of the most difficult

00:07:40.168 --> 00:07:44.278
styles to master, because all
these things are a language.

00:07:44.308 --> 00:07:48.168
Blues playing, they're all just languages,
right? It's like, just like you'd learn

00:07:48.228 --> 00:07:52.048
any type of language. My dad loved

00:07:52.068 --> 00:07:55.988
bebop. Now, when I was a little kid
and he's listening to these bebop

00:07:56.068 --> 00:07:59.958
records, whether it's Charlie
Parker or Dizzy Gillespie

00:08:00.028 --> 00:08:03.888
or Oscar Peterson, Joe
Pass, great jazz guitar

00:08:04.028 --> 00:08:07.968
player, I'm just hearing this stuff. I don't know
any different. My dad was not a musician, but for

00:08:08.088 --> 00:08:11.568
some reason, he liked
incredibly sophisticated-

00:08:11.608 --> 00:08:16.068
... music that was very technical. And,

00:08:17.768 --> 00:08:22.468
I just heard it and just was like, "Oh,
yeah, okay, cool." And not realizing that

00:08:23.548 --> 00:08:28.048
it was developing my ear, because I
really, bebop is one of the hardest

00:08:29.108 --> 00:08:33.098
to improvise in that style, in
that language of bebop. It's

00:08:33.308 --> 00:08:41.538
very difficult to do. And hearing
it as a kid is one of the things

00:08:41.648 --> 00:08:48.148
that I think enables you, just like
languages, enables you to learn it

00:08:49.008 --> 00:08:52.957
as opposed to somebody that's never been exposed
to it and tries to learn it as a teenager.

00:08:53.108 --> 00:08:57.068
So I think it's very similar to
learning languages, which kinda

00:08:57.148 --> 00:09:01.068
is like my theory on perfect pitch,
that every child is born with

00:09:01.108 --> 00:09:05.528
perfect pitch. And they start to
lose the ability around nine months-

00:09:05.608 --> 00:09:09.588
... when people become
culturally bound listeners,

00:09:09.748 --> 00:09:13.308
when babies do. They start
out as citizens of the

00:09:13.388 --> 00:09:17.028
world, you know? They can,
they have the the neural

00:09:17.088 --> 00:09:23.838
pathways to hear the sounds, the phonemes
of all 6,500 languages spoken on Earth.

00:09:23.848 --> 00:09:26.928
But then around nine months, they
begin to lose that ability and

00:09:26.988 --> 00:09:30.648
they, when they become these
culturally bound listeners, there's a

00:09:30.728 --> 00:09:36.208
great YouTube video with this woman,
Patricia Kuhl. She's a language researcher.

00:09:37.308 --> 00:09:40.177
And I watched this, The
linguistic genius of babies.

00:09:40.228 --> 00:09:43.908
I saw this in 2010, this lecture
that she did, like a TED

00:09:43.968 --> 00:09:47.648
Talk, and she talks about this,
that kids, they did a, an

00:09:47.688 --> 00:09:51.008
experiment. They exposed kids to
Mandarin three times a week for

00:09:51.168 --> 00:09:52.648
25-minute sessions, just a

00:09:54.028 --> 00:09:58.008
person speaking Mandarin to
these babies. And they were able

00:09:58.088 --> 00:10:05.218
to recognize the sounds, the phonemes
of that language even later on.

00:10:05.288 --> 00:10:09.108
And when I realized that
my son Dylan had perfect

00:10:09.148 --> 00:10:13.338
pitch, I thought, "Why does Dylan
have perfect pitch but no one

00:10:14.768 --> 00:10:18.728
in my family had ever had perfect
pitch?" And I thought, "Well, it must be

00:10:18.808 --> 00:10:20.568
because of the things I exposed to him

00:10:22.088 --> 00:10:25.608
prenatally and then in the
first nine months of his life."

00:10:25.668 --> 00:10:27.717
'Cause that's the only
way I could explain it.

00:10:27.728 --> 00:10:31.588
- We're gonna return to Joe Pass. We gotta
go to Dylan. You mentioned Dylan. I guess

00:10:31.648 --> 00:10:35.238
that's in part one of
the origin stories of

00:10:35.288 --> 00:10:39.148
you putting out videos into the
world, is the early videos you

00:10:39.168 --> 00:10:42.918
did with Dylan, a set of videos on his
perfect pitch. And for people who don't

00:10:42.948 --> 00:10:45.698
know, maybe you can speak to
what perfect pitch means.

00:10:45.788 --> 00:10:53.628
- It's the ability to identify any note
without a reference tone. So you can play,

00:10:54.628 --> 00:10:58.488
it doesn't matter how quickly they
are, that a person with perfect pitch

00:10:58.528 --> 00:11:03.088
can hear a note and immediately
identify it. Or a collection of notes.

00:11:03.148 --> 00:11:06.368
- And taking a tangent upon a tangent,
you also have a course on ear training.

00:11:06.408 --> 00:11:08.568
- Yes, but my course is for relative pitch-

00:11:08.588 --> 00:11:08.597
- Relative pitch

00:11:08.597 --> 00:11:10.148
- ... not to be confused with perfect pitch.

00:11:10.308 --> 00:11:14.108
- Is it fair to say that relative pitch, as
far as the thing you would learn, is more

00:11:14.128 --> 00:11:14.688
useful-

00:11:14.728 --> 00:11:14.798
- Yes

00:11:14.808 --> 00:11:15.688
- ... for musicians?

00:11:15.728 --> 00:11:15.928
- Yes.

00:11:15.968 --> 00:11:17.488
- Can you explain the
difference between the two?

00:11:17.608 --> 00:11:23.788
- Relative pitch is basically learning
how to identify pitches relative to

00:11:23.888 --> 00:11:27.768
a stated tonic or something that
you've heard, or just relative

00:11:27.808 --> 00:11:31.428
to each other. If you hear a note
and then you hear another note after

00:11:31.488 --> 00:11:35.388
it, you can recognize, let's say, it's
a minor third interval. So if you're on

00:11:35.428 --> 00:11:39.508
the note A, the next note would be C.
So once you're given a reference note,

00:11:40.368 --> 00:11:43.688
you can use relative pitch to identify the

00:11:43.768 --> 00:11:46.168
relative nature from one pitch to another.

00:11:46.388 --> 00:11:51.128
- And of course, intervals make up
scales, and intervals make up chords-

00:11:51.138 --> 00:11:51.368
- Chords, yup.

00:11:51.608 --> 00:11:56.368
- ... and so that if you
develop it to any degree

00:11:57.208 --> 00:12:01.768
relative pitch, you can understand,
you can hear the music better.

00:12:01.808 --> 00:12:02.768
- Yes.

00:12:03.016 --> 00:12:06.876
- Um, what does it take since we're
taking a tangent on a tangent, what's

00:12:06.956 --> 00:12:10.896
what does it take to train
your ear? What's a TL;DR

00:12:10.916 --> 00:12:13.956
on the course before
people go out and sign up?

00:12:13.976 --> 00:12:17.536
- It's just practice basically.
You start with intervals.

00:12:17.576 --> 00:12:21.536
Typically, with small intervals like minor
second, major second. So minor second would

00:12:21.556 --> 00:12:23.636
be a half-step, major second
would be a whole-step.

00:12:23.676 --> 00:12:26.746
- Are you listening to the tone one after
the other or two of them together?

00:12:26.776 --> 00:12:31.466
- Both. So played separately it's called
melodic intervals, right, like a melody?

00:12:31.496 --> 00:12:35.216
And harmonic intervals are played like a
harmony, together. So you have to be able to

00:12:35.236 --> 00:12:38.096
identify them both, both ways.

00:12:38.116 --> 00:12:41.506
- What's an early journey? Like, we'll give
people a preview of what they should...

00:12:41.556 --> 00:12:44.766
Like, what does that look like?
What does practice look like?

00:12:44.796 --> 00:12:48.256
- Well, my course, it will play
you an interval, and then you

00:12:48.316 --> 00:12:52.236
identify it by clicking on whether
it's, you know, a major third, or minor

00:12:52.296 --> 00:12:56.156
third, or major sixth, or minor sixth, or
perfect fifth, or tritone, whatever it is.

00:12:56.176 --> 00:13:02.756
And it will teach you gradually, over
time, how to recognize all the intervals.

00:13:02.776 --> 00:13:09.036
- So you listen to a melodic interval
or a harmonic interval. How quickly

00:13:09.596 --> 00:13:13.336
does the ear in the various
age groups that we humans are

00:13:13.436 --> 00:13:17.256
in, how quickly does the
ear learn the different

00:13:17.296 --> 00:13:22.996
intervals? Is it a week? Two weeks?
A month? Two months? Five years?

00:13:23.056 --> 00:13:26.806
- I think you'd do it pretty quickly. Within,
you know, if you practice, within a couple of

00:13:26.836 --> 00:13:32.976
months, you can really make a lot of
progress on it, if you practice daily.

00:13:33.016 --> 00:13:36.696
- What benefit does it have to
you as a musician in general?

00:13:36.736 --> 00:13:40.266
- Well, it's great if you wanna hear a chord
progression if you're trying to figure out a song.

00:13:40.956 --> 00:13:44.756
And you can say, "Oh, that's going from the
six minor chord, or the four major, to the

00:13:44.836 --> 00:13:46.796
five major, to the one major."

00:13:46.816 --> 00:13:50.796
And you can just identify it immediately, and then you
figure out what the first chord is, then you know what

00:13:50.836 --> 00:13:54.276
the rest of the chords are 'cause
they're in relation to whatever

00:13:54.336 --> 00:13:58.296
that first chord is. And for
learning solos, for example,

00:13:58.336 --> 00:14:01.236
or learning melodies, being
able to sound something out.

00:14:01.616 --> 00:14:04.856
- Now, do you recommend people
couple that with music

00:14:04.896 --> 00:14:09.516
theory in terms of education,
the education journey?

00:14:09.556 --> 00:14:14.716
- They have to be taught together because
these terms are really music theory, right?

00:14:14.756 --> 00:14:18.556
Those intervals, major second, minor
second, major third, minor third, perfect

00:14:18.596 --> 00:14:22.546
fourth. So as you're doing that, and then

00:14:23.416 --> 00:14:26.976
you... Once you learn
the intervals, the 12

00:14:27.016 --> 00:14:30.356
intervals in an octave, then you
learn 'em both melodically and

00:14:30.376 --> 00:14:34.016
harmonically, so played together
and separate. Then you learn

00:14:34.136 --> 00:14:37.956
chords, and so then you learn
to identify major, minor,

00:14:37.996 --> 00:14:41.776
diminished, augmented, suspended chords,
things like that. Well, you're basically

00:14:41.836 --> 00:14:45.796
learning music theory at the same time
with that. 'Cause learning... Music theory

00:14:45.806 --> 00:14:48.656
is just the name of things in music.

00:14:48.716 --> 00:14:51.876
- So there's the sound of things.

00:14:51.896 --> 00:14:56.896
There's the name of things, and then
there's the haptic, like playing the thing-

00:14:57.116 --> 00:14:57.176
- Right

00:14:57.196 --> 00:15:01.156
- ... probably. So playing chords, playing
scales, you have, I believe, a course on scales

00:15:01.256 --> 00:15:06.336
and on chords? Okay. Since we're doing the
tangent, let's go. How do you recommend

00:15:06.396 --> 00:15:09.676
people... There's a bunch of people
listening to this that are curious about

00:15:10.656 --> 00:15:14.566
how they can start in playing guitar,
maybe even playing piano and maybe

00:15:14.566 --> 00:15:18.256
maybe playing other instruments. Although
guitar, of course, is the greatest

00:15:18.276 --> 00:15:19.736
instrument of all time.

00:15:19.756 --> 00:15:23.236
What are the early steps of that journey?
What do you recommend people do in general?

00:15:23.256 --> 00:15:25.276
- Well, if you're a beginner

00:15:26.256 --> 00:15:30.156
getting a good beginner guitar course and
learning, first of all, the open chords

00:15:30.356 --> 00:15:34.276
in first position. A lot of songs
can be played that way. A lot

00:15:34.296 --> 00:15:38.926
of old songs can be played that way,
maybe not new modern songs necessarily.

00:15:38.976 --> 00:15:43.996
- So learning a few chords and with an
eye towards maybe playing a song?

00:15:44.036 --> 00:15:47.896
- Yeah. With an eye towards... You learn the
chord shapes and you learn how to strum

00:15:47.996 --> 00:15:51.646
basic patterns to begin
with. I think the first

00:15:51.716 --> 00:15:55.636
thing for learning guitar
is actually how to position

00:15:55.676 --> 00:16:00.386
your fingers so that you don't mute
strings that you don't want to mute.

00:16:00.436 --> 00:16:03.916
That's the hardest thing for people to
do, basically, is to get their fingers

00:16:04.076 --> 00:16:07.866
arched to where they... If you're
playing a C major chord, your

00:16:07.936 --> 00:16:11.836
index finger's on the first fret of the B string,
and you have to have that open E string ringing

00:16:11.876 --> 00:16:14.616
there. And it's hard for
people to make those micro-

00:16:14.996 --> 00:16:18.405
microadjustments. You take it for granted,
like, you've been playing guitar-

00:16:18.716 --> 00:16:21.716
... for, I don't know, how
many years? Forever, right?

00:16:21.736 --> 00:16:22.466
- Forever, yeah.

00:16:22.496 --> 00:16:26.296
- And you don't even think about stuff like
that when you're playing a guitar solo.

00:16:26.356 --> 00:16:31.596
Every little thing that you do if you're
playing your Comfortably Numb guitar solo-

00:16:31.606 --> 00:16:35.596
... you have to, out of mid-air, strike
the string that your finger's on to play

00:16:35.696 --> 00:16:39.196
the note. And these are all fine
adjustments that you're doing.

00:16:39.396 --> 00:16:43.216
- I'm just a hobbyist recreational player,
but it... Wow, you're taking me all the way

00:16:43.256 --> 00:16:47.056
back. You're right, it's the haptic, the

00:16:47.136 --> 00:16:50.256
physical aspect of it is really
tricky. Comfortably Numb is a good

00:16:50.296 --> 00:16:54.236
example, but if you do lead,
you have to get a super

00:16:54.316 --> 00:16:58.176
clean sound. Now, that's both
when you're playing fast, you

00:16:58.216 --> 00:17:02.096
want it to be super precise, but when
you play slow, when you have one note,

00:17:02.116 --> 00:17:06.626
and you're holding it, and you're bending
it- ... it better be really clean.

00:17:06.656 --> 00:17:10.436
And for that, it's... I guess you have
to really place the finger in the right

00:17:10.556 --> 00:17:13.476
place. Plus, there's
the... Well, there's the

00:17:13.536 --> 00:17:17.396
calluses, so it doesn't hurt. And then the

00:17:17.436 --> 00:17:20.756
positioning of the string
on the curvature of-

00:17:20.796 --> 00:17:24.716
... of the finger. Where does it fall?
Like, how much do you bend the finger?

00:17:24.736 --> 00:17:27.966
- You have to have enough flesh
on it to actually raise

00:17:28.096 --> 00:17:31.676
the- raise the string
and pitch. Otherwise it-

00:17:31.716 --> 00:17:35.696
- Yeah, 'cause you're lifting it with part
of the flesh. And of course, you have to

00:17:35.736 --> 00:17:39.436
decide, depends on how OCD you
are, do you wanna be, like, the

00:17:39.556 --> 00:17:43.296
perfect, the proper musician?
Or do you wanna do a

00:17:43.336 --> 00:17:46.636
Hendrix? So the thumb over the top.

00:17:46.696 --> 00:17:48.096
- Way over the top, yes.

00:17:48.116 --> 00:17:51.836
- And so, like, you... if you have
a fretboard here, I think the

00:17:51.916 --> 00:17:58.736
more, like, classical guitarists, the
very proper, perfect perpendicular

00:17:58.816 --> 00:18:02.796
alignment of the fingertips
to the fretboard, versus,

00:18:02.816 --> 00:18:10.448
like, Hendrix's, like, "Fuck it. You
nerds. I'm gonna do it." With the

00:18:10.588 --> 00:18:14.148
messiness is part of the
magic. Of course, like

00:18:14.648 --> 00:18:18.388
B.B. King is also kind of
messy looking in terms of his

00:18:18.408 --> 00:18:22.508
positioning of the fingers, but
his tone is incredibly clean.

00:18:22.568 --> 00:18:23.448
- Yes, super clean.

00:18:23.488 --> 00:18:27.428
- So, like, that teaches you that
maybe any position can converge

00:18:27.448 --> 00:18:30.228
towards a super clean tone. You
just have to figure it out.

00:18:30.288 --> 00:18:32.248
- I think a lot of it has to do with

00:18:33.308 --> 00:18:37.098
how they wear their guitars. If you wear your guitar
low, if you're Hendrix and you're wearing your

00:18:37.108 --> 00:18:37.528
guitar

00:18:37.848 --> 00:18:38.108
- That's true

00:18:38.118 --> 00:18:43.968
- ... if you're wearing it lower,
then you can't get your fingers

00:18:44.808 --> 00:18:49.728
on top of it like that. And the thumb
acts as a way to mute the lower

00:18:49.908 --> 00:18:53.768
strings from ringing if you're playing
through a loud amplifier. So there's

00:18:53.828 --> 00:18:57.798
so many other micro-adjustments when you're
playing leads, 'cause you have to kind

00:18:57.808 --> 00:19:01.198
of mute the other strings that
are... so they don't ring out-

00:19:01.348 --> 00:19:05.268
... if you're playing the first note in
Comfortably Numb and the solo at the

00:19:05.408 --> 00:19:09.308
end, and you're at the ninth fret
of the G string, and you bend that

00:19:09.318 --> 00:19:13.968
... if you bend that G string and you
accidentally hit the B string under it

00:19:14.328 --> 00:19:18.048
... you don't want that ringing. So you have
to kind of angle your index finger so it

00:19:18.068 --> 00:19:18.468
- To mute

00:19:18.728 --> 00:19:19.858
- ... to mute that.

00:19:19.858 --> 00:19:23.788
So all these micro-adjustments that you don't
even think about... I mean, you're not thinking

00:19:23.848 --> 00:19:27.338
about that, Lex, when you're playing
it. You've done it so many times that

00:19:27.908 --> 00:19:31.808
these things are just part of
your brain. That's why this is

00:19:32.028 --> 00:19:36.708
such a great brain developer
for kids to learn instruments.

00:19:36.988 --> 00:19:40.628
- Yeah, of course, you have to solve that
puzzle. It must be really frustrating in the

00:19:40.668 --> 00:19:46.558
beginning, like holding a chord. Like
all of 'em, and it hurts too, right?

00:19:46.568 --> 00:19:46.938
- It does hurt.

00:19:46.938 --> 00:19:47.968
- If you're doing acoustic guitar.

00:19:47.988 --> 00:19:50.998
- Not for that long,
though. For like a week.

00:19:51.168 --> 00:19:51.908
- Couple, couple, yeah.

00:19:51.968 --> 00:19:53.088
- Couple weeks.

00:19:53.128 --> 00:19:53.598
- Couple.

00:19:55.068 --> 00:19:58.388
- I don't want to discourage anyone, you
know. It's actually pretty easy to learn

00:19:58.908 --> 00:19:59.808
basic stuff.

00:19:59.868 --> 00:20:03.308
- Right, but the pain is temporary, I
guess is the point I'm trying to make.

00:20:03.348 --> 00:20:03.938
- It is.

00:20:04.648 --> 00:20:08.508
- Uh, so what else? So the
physical component, play a few

00:20:08.568 --> 00:20:11.668
chords, where does the journey
continue if you're learning guitar?

00:20:11.708 --> 00:20:15.508
- Well then, it's like if you play
electric guitar, then you get into

00:20:15.568 --> 00:20:18.978
single note playing and stuff like that. That's
where it gets, to me, where it gets really

00:20:19.008 --> 00:20:22.908
fun. You know, you have single
note playing with riffs,

00:20:22.948 --> 00:20:26.788
if you think of Back in
Black, right, that has a riff

00:20:26.828 --> 00:20:30.628
embedded in the actual melody. Or many

00:20:30.668 --> 00:20:34.188
songs that have riffs, the
Hendrix stuff that has chordal

00:20:34.288 --> 00:20:38.188
riffs, and you're moving up the neck and,

00:20:38.268 --> 00:20:42.148
Involving all the fingers and things like
that. So there's... it really depends

00:20:42.188 --> 00:20:44.748
on what you wanna, what
styles you wanna play.

00:20:44.788 --> 00:20:48.268
- So you're thinking about song learning.
So different components of song learning.

00:20:48.288 --> 00:20:52.808
So riffs in songs, lead-in songs.

00:20:52.868 --> 00:20:56.448
- And then you have finger picking, if you
have Stairway to Heaven, songs like that.

00:20:56.488 --> 00:20:59.948
How 'bout wanting to learn that, that
involves finger picking, because the, you

00:21:00.008 --> 00:21:03.988
have to isolate certain notes
of the chord and play two

00:21:04.008 --> 00:21:07.198
together, you know, and multiple times.

00:21:07.228 --> 00:21:11.168
- There's a few crossroads where
you get to select things. Uh,

00:21:11.268 --> 00:21:15.008
so I guess you're speaking to the fact there's
a... if you're righty, there's a right hand

00:21:15.488 --> 00:21:18.608
that you can use your fingers
or you can use a pick.

00:21:18.648 --> 00:21:19.208
- Correct.

00:21:19.217 --> 00:21:20.878
- And that's a choice you make.

00:21:20.888 --> 00:21:24.838
- And sometimes you use both, 'cause in Stairway
to Heaven, you're using the fingers at

00:21:24.848 --> 00:21:28.777
the beginning, or fingers
and pick, hybrid, they call

00:21:28.788 --> 00:21:32.588
it hybrid picking, and then later
on, you're using the pick to

00:21:32.608 --> 00:21:34.748
flat pick the picking patterns.

00:21:34.808 --> 00:21:38.768
- On the music theory front, do you recommend
people learn scales and chords and like the

00:21:38.777 --> 00:21:39.988
theory of it?

00:21:40.108 --> 00:21:45.138
- Uh, later on I would say. I wouldn't
say necessarily right off the bat.

00:21:45.868 --> 00:21:49.768
I think learning songs is the
first thing that you should

00:21:49.788 --> 00:21:52.048
do 'cause that you want
to keep people motivated.

00:21:52.088 --> 00:21:54.908
- So you get them to like fall in
love with music and playing?

00:21:55.988 --> 00:21:55.997
- Yes.

00:21:56.048 --> 00:21:59.608
- All right. And that takes a
couple months, three months?

00:21:59.618 --> 00:22:01.568
- Depends on how motivated they are.

00:22:02.368 --> 00:22:04.328
- So you recommend practicing,
what, every day?

00:22:04.368 --> 00:22:08.328
- Every day. My son, Dylan, when he started
learning the guitar a couple years

00:22:08.368 --> 00:22:11.908
ago, I said, "It's better to practice

00:22:12.728 --> 00:22:16.388
10 minutes a day, seven days a
week than to practice one day

00:22:16.808 --> 00:22:19.388
for an hour, which is roughly
the same amount of time."

00:22:19.468 --> 00:22:23.347
- Yeah, but it usually turns into
something longer. But otherwise,

00:22:23.388 --> 00:22:27.308
like, if you're a busy life,
you know, taking a day off,

00:22:27.368 --> 00:22:31.248
that day turns into a week, and then a week turns into
a month, and all of a sudden you haven't touched the

00:22:31.288 --> 00:22:32.968
instrument for months.

00:22:33.008 --> 00:22:36.988
- Which is why I leave my guitar
on a stand all the time, so

00:22:37.028 --> 00:22:40.788
that if I walk by it, I'm like, "Oh, okay, I'll
just pick it up for a second." Then that second

00:22:40.848 --> 00:22:43.868
turns into 10 minutes,
and an hour, two hours.

00:22:43.908 --> 00:22:47.808
- All right, we gotta talk about this Dylan
video. So this might be one of the earliest-

00:22:47.828 --> 00:22:48.688
- That's the first one.

00:22:48.708 --> 00:22:50.578
- That's the first video on the channel.

00:22:50.588 --> 00:22:54.498
- It was, it was actually before the channel,
'cause this actually blew up on Facebook-

00:22:54.498 --> 00:22:54.508
- Facebook

00:22:54.688 --> 00:22:57.428
- ... and then I put it on YouTube after.

00:22:59.028 --> 00:23:00.688
- Uh, so if it's okay?

00:23:00.728 --> 00:23:04.178
- Yeah. Okay, Dylan, we're gonna do
the hardest ear training test of all

00:23:04.288 --> 00:23:06.428
time. Are you ready?

00:23:06.488 --> 00:23:10.228
- Ready. Oh.

00:23:10.488 --> 00:23:12.648
- Now, I... just a quick backstory on this.

00:23:12.708 --> 00:23:16.978
I made this for my friend Shane's wife
who wanted to see... 'cause Shane was a-

00:23:18.248 --> 00:23:22.228
a friend that I was
producing, and he was there,

00:23:22.268 --> 00:23:26.158
and Dylan had come down the day, in the day, and
I said, "Oh, check this out," and I played this

00:23:26.228 --> 00:23:29.618
stuff. He's like, "That's amazing. Can
you make a video so I can show my wife?"

00:23:30.608 --> 00:23:34.358
And I was on the way to a school board meeting,
'cause I was on the school board at Dylan's

00:23:34.368 --> 00:23:35.098
school-

00:23:35.488 --> 00:23:39.408
... and I said, "Hey, Dylan, come downstairs.
I want to make this video. It'll take one

00:23:39.468 --> 00:23:43.368
minute, just need to do this thing for my
friend, Shane." And he's like, "I don't want

00:23:43.488 --> 00:23:47.308
to." And I said, "Come on, this'll take
one minute." "I don't want to." So I said

00:23:47.468 --> 00:23:51.058
to my wife, I'm like, "Nina, would you tell
Dylan to come downstairs? I want to do this

00:23:51.088 --> 00:23:55.048
video. It'll take one minute." She's like,

00:23:55.068 --> 00:23:58.158
Dylan, go downstairs." And he had,
he has a mouthful of candy there-

00:23:58.158 --> 00:24:01.948
... 'cause he was eating candy. So if
you look at him, he literally has a

00:24:01.988 --> 00:24:03.658
mouthful of candy while he's doing this.

00:24:04.248 --> 00:24:08.408
- And we should say, on
Facebook it went quite viral.

00:24:08.448 --> 00:24:12.312
- Yeah, like got... I don't know, 80
million views. Something like, it

00:24:12.352 --> 00:24:15.832
had like 250,000 comments.
Something like that. Insane.

00:24:15.872 --> 00:24:16.952
- How old is Dylan here?

00:24:16.972 --> 00:24:17.852
- He's eight.

00:24:17.892 --> 00:24:18.532
- Eight years old?

00:24:18.572 --> 00:24:18.902
- Yeah.

00:24:18.952 --> 00:24:22.612
- Can you actually give some more backstory about,
like, how you discovered that Dylan has perfect

00:24:22.652 --> 00:24:23.092
pitch?

00:24:23.172 --> 00:24:27.022
- So when Dylan was about two, he... I was

00:24:27.052 --> 00:24:31.042
doing a FaceTime with my brother
Jon, and I was like, "Check this

00:24:31.132 --> 00:24:35.092
out, Jon." And I played the Stone in
Love, Neal Schon's solo from Journey,

00:24:35.132 --> 00:24:38.052
and I was like, "Check this
out." And Dylan would sing along

00:24:38.092 --> 00:24:42.072
and my brother Jon was like, "Wow,

00:24:42.092 --> 00:24:45.802
Dylan can sing all the notes." And I was like,
"Yeah." Then I played Black Dog, Zeppelin-

00:24:45.802 --> 00:24:49.752
... and Dylan would sing that. And it's like,
"Dylan's got a good ear." Then Jon and I

00:24:49.772 --> 00:24:53.592
were like, "Well, we have good ears, too." So it was probably...
Maybe we could have done that when we were that age.

00:24:53.612 --> 00:24:57.392
So a couple years, more years goes by. Well,
he was about three and a half, and I'm in the

00:24:57.452 --> 00:25:01.332
car. I was like, "Dylan, sing the Star
Wars theme." And he sings it, and I'm

00:25:01.392 --> 00:25:05.372
like, "That's in the right
key." And I checked. I

00:25:05.572 --> 00:25:09.372
play it on my phone, and I was like, "Oh my
gosh." Then I ask him, "Play... Sing the Superman

00:25:09.452 --> 00:25:13.322
theme." Because we'd been listening to
John Williams soundtracks the week before,

00:25:13.832 --> 00:25:17.592
and he sings that. And that was in
the right key. And I ask him another

00:25:17.652 --> 00:25:21.432
song. So I turn the car around, I
go back to the studio. I go to the

00:25:21.472 --> 00:25:24.912
piano, I hit the note B-flat,
and Dylan says, "Star

00:25:24.992 --> 00:25:28.912
Wars." Star Wars starts on a
big B-flat major chord, but

00:25:28.952 --> 00:25:32.912
it's the note B-flat is the main one
that you hear. And then I play the

00:25:32.932 --> 00:25:36.492
note G, and he goes, "Superman." And that's
the first note in the trumpet part of the-

00:25:36.502 --> 00:25:40.482
...of the Superman theme. And then I
realized that he had perfect pitch, and then

00:25:40.532 --> 00:25:43.772
in five minutes, I taught him
the name of the 12 notes.

00:25:43.812 --> 00:25:46.312
Which he already knew, but he
just didn't know the names.

00:25:46.332 --> 00:25:48.152
- Oh, so you just associate the names—

00:25:48.172 --> 00:25:48.212
- Yeah

00:25:48.222 --> 00:25:51.892
- ...of the thing he knows. What do you think
is this in his mind? 'Cause it's not just

00:25:51.972 --> 00:25:56.432
individual notes. He can, like,
hear everything. What is that?

00:25:56.452 --> 00:26:01.872
- He doesn't see colors. He just says
every note sounds completely different.

00:26:01.932 --> 00:26:06.592
- Wow. Like you said, maybe
it's a language thing.

00:26:06.612 --> 00:26:09.732
Because it really is a... He
just learned the language.

00:26:09.772 --> 00:26:10.522
- Yeah, the language.

00:26:10.532 --> 00:26:10.542
- There's-

00:26:10.552 --> 00:26:14.532
- It's like, it's like perfect
it's like native music

00:26:14.572 --> 00:26:16.472
fluency, if you think of it like that.

00:26:16.512 --> 00:26:18.332
- So let's listen to some of this.

00:26:18.352 --> 00:26:22.112
- Turn around. Here we go. As fast as you can, we're going
to start with single notes, then we're going to do some

00:26:22.292 --> 00:26:30.432
intervals, then chords. Okay, here we
go. A. C-sharp. B-flat. C. D. A-flat.

00:26:30.512 --> 00:26:32.552
- Okay, good. Two notes at once. Here we go.

00:26:33.452 --> 00:26:41.462
- C-flat. Great. How about this? B-flat, A.
Great. What about this? B-flat, A-flat.

00:26:41.652 --> 00:26:42.792
- This is incredible.

00:26:42.812 --> 00:26:47.572
- Great. How about this? C, B-flat.

00:26:47.612 --> 00:26:50.092
- And then how about this?

00:26:50.132 --> 00:26:58.692
- E-flat. What is it? E, E-flat. Correct.
Okay. He's, he's annoyed. He's annoyed.

00:26:58.712 --> 00:27:02.652
The part of this, when I play
these next chords, that's really

00:27:02.752 --> 00:27:05.962
I think why the video went so
viral, the next part of this.

00:27:05.962 --> 00:27:09.952
Where I play these super complex polychords.
Okay, I'm going to do some polychords

00:27:10.032 --> 00:27:12.692
for you. These are really going to
be hard. You ready? What's this?

00:27:14.232 --> 00:27:22.752
C augmented over D-flat augmented. Okay,
sing a B-flat. Mm. Very good. What's this

00:27:22.812 --> 00:27:37.272
chord? Uh... A-flat— Oh, A-flat major
over A major. Great, sing an F-sharp. Mm.

00:27:37.372 --> 00:27:46.172
Excellent. What's this chord? A minor over
D-flat major. Great. What's this chord?

00:27:50.372 --> 00:27:54.202
E add 9 over F major. Excellent. E add 9 over F
major. So I had to look at my hand to make sure that

00:27:54.232 --> 00:27:57.712
that's what it was— ...'cause
they're all in inversions.

00:27:57.772 --> 00:28:01.632
So I think the reason that this
went so viral is that the more that

00:28:01.712 --> 00:28:05.512
someone knew about music, the
more that they shared the

00:28:05.552 --> 00:28:12.732
video. Because these polychords... So
the people that were the best musicians

00:28:12.792 --> 00:28:16.711
were li- were... Would... Looked at it and
was like, "Oh my God." You know, it's C

00:28:16.792 --> 00:28:19.262
augmented over D-flat augmented.

00:28:19.352 --> 00:28:23.232
Um, and the the second chord
was A-flat major over A

00:28:23.312 --> 00:28:27.192
major, but they were both in inversion,
right? So it was like a first

00:28:27.232 --> 00:28:31.221
inversion A-flat major chord, first
inversion A major chord. And then

00:28:31.812 --> 00:28:35.762
an A minor over D-flat major,
and then E add 9 over F major.

00:28:35.792 --> 00:28:38.472
And for an eight-year-old...
I mean, for anyone—

00:28:38.652 --> 00:28:42.392
... plus they're all close-voiced. They're
all just right next to each other.

00:28:42.432 --> 00:28:42.852
- Yeah, yeah.

00:28:42.892 --> 00:28:46.552
- It's not like, you know, where you can hear them
clear. It's all in the mid-range of the piano.

00:28:46.592 --> 00:28:50.492
So you have to really listen and
and you have to di—... He has to

00:28:50.532 --> 00:28:54.212
dissect each one. Like, what are
the notes being played there,

00:28:54.272 --> 00:28:58.092
and and what is... Like, what's
the theory? 'Cause he's actually

00:28:58.172 --> 00:29:00.692
using music theory— ... to dissect them.

00:29:00.732 --> 00:29:06.052
- It must be in his brain, those components
of the chords all sound different. Like-

00:29:06.062 --> 00:29:07.512
... very clearly different.

00:29:07.552 --> 00:29:08.592
- Yes.

00:29:08.652 --> 00:29:12.332
- It's truly incredible. The human mind's
incredible. So you're saying, like, some

00:29:12.452 --> 00:29:18.252
part of that is the things you hear
in the first few months of life?

00:29:18.412 --> 00:29:22.252
- I did a thing where I played what
I call high information music.

00:29:22.292 --> 00:29:29.712
High information music would be Bach,
Well-Tempered Clavier, fugues, yeah, any-

00:29:29.732 --> 00:29:31.552
anything Bach.

00:29:31.572 --> 00:29:35.432
And I would play the Well-Tempered
Clavier, and I would play... I have a,

00:29:35.532 --> 00:29:39.312
a friend who... Turkish pianist who's
one of the greatest improvisers I've

00:29:39.352 --> 00:29:40.912
ever heard. His name's Aydin Esen.

00:29:41.792 --> 00:29:45.002
And I would play Aydin's
improvisations for Dylan. It had very

00:29:45.112 --> 00:29:52.472
sophisticated harmony and linear things
in it. And Keith Jarrett, and mainly

00:29:52.552 --> 00:29:56.412
jazz, classical, and modern
classical music. And then,

00:29:56.452 --> 00:30:00.352
then we would play, listen to rock music once he
was born. I'm talking on my wife's stomach before

00:30:00.372 --> 00:30:05.412
Dylan was born— ... starting at
15 weeks, for 30 minutes a night.

00:30:05.472 --> 00:30:09.412
And then when Dylan was born, I
would sit with him for an hour

00:30:09.492 --> 00:30:11.542
every morning and listen to music—

00:30:11.612 --> 00:30:15.322
... and I would look at him.
In order for this for them

00:30:15.452 --> 00:30:19.256
to... hear these phonemes
apparently and develop

00:30:19.296 --> 00:30:22.556
this language, or get the...
The language acquisition has

00:30:22.596 --> 00:30:25.946
to involve the social brain.

00:30:26.096 --> 00:30:29.796
So, when kids look at you, when a baby's
looking at you, they're looking at your

00:30:29.856 --> 00:30:33.616
mouth and they're getting social
cues from that. And this is

00:30:33.696 --> 00:30:40.936
also another component of saying
"This is where this word stops or

00:30:41.036 --> 00:30:44.676
starts and stops. These are
how this, the phonemes are

00:30:44.756 --> 00:30:48.546
separated from one another. These are how
they're connected." So I believe that

00:30:48.636 --> 00:30:52.576
all kids are born with perfect pitch
and then around nine months they begin

00:30:52.616 --> 00:30:56.456
to lose it. If you don't engage their
social brain, making these pitches

00:30:56.516 --> 00:31:00.906
know ... I never played pitches for Dylan
and said, "This is a C, this is a B flat-"

00:31:00.906 --> 00:31:03.996
"... this is a G." I just played complex-

00:31:04.036 --> 00:31:07.556
...high-information music
form. And played with him.

00:31:07.596 --> 00:31:11.816
- And that applies maybe even more
generally to high-information language.

00:31:11.856 --> 00:31:13.436
- Yes.

00:31:13.496 --> 00:31:17.116
- And it starts before
they're born. I think I saw

00:31:17.196 --> 00:31:20.496
some of these incredible
scientists that work

00:31:21.276 --> 00:31:25.056
on the neuroscience, the
neurobiology, psychology of language

00:31:25.256 --> 00:31:29.236
in early life. I think a big part

00:31:29.336 --> 00:31:33.676
is you, in the mother's stomach
you're listening to the mother speak.

00:31:33.736 --> 00:31:35.196
- Yes. That's right.

00:31:35.216 --> 00:31:39.706
- So, like, that's how on the language side
you're picking up the language already.

00:31:39.706 --> 00:31:43.196
- That's right. And you're picking
up the music, musical language.

00:31:43.206 --> 00:31:46.186
So, native music fluency,
you could call it.

00:31:46.216 --> 00:31:49.736
- So if the mother's sitting back
and listening to Bach and some

00:31:50.396 --> 00:31:54.416
bebop jazz, you have a, you
have a pretty good chance.

00:31:54.496 --> 00:31:55.996
- Much better chance.

00:31:56.056 --> 00:32:02.806
- Okay. All right. So as we unwind our
way back Joe Pass and bebop. You were

00:32:02.816 --> 00:32:06.456
You were funny enough
talking about what is bebop

00:32:06.516 --> 00:32:10.276
jazz and, and that would be people like
Joe Pass. And in your own life, your

00:32:10.336 --> 00:32:14.136
dad was somehow listening
to that kind of incredibly

00:32:14.256 --> 00:32:16.276
complex and sophisticated music-

00:32:16.296 --> 00:32:17.516
- But wasn't a musician.

00:32:17.556 --> 00:32:17.946
- Wasn't a musician.

00:32:17.946 --> 00:32:21.706
- Which was very weird. We
never... I have six siblings

00:32:21.876 --> 00:32:26.856
and we could never figure out why
dad liked really sophisticated jazz.

00:32:26.876 --> 00:32:28.396
- We just took it for granted at that time.

00:32:28.436 --> 00:32:32.236
- Yeah, just took it for granted. And
my dad passed away in 2004 and we

00:32:32.276 --> 00:32:35.836
never really talked about that, but he and I
used to listen to music together all the time.

00:32:35.856 --> 00:32:39.256
We'd put on a record, I'd sit on one
side of the room, he'd sit on the

00:32:39.316 --> 00:32:44.656
other and not say a word. Listen through
the whole side A. I'd go flip it over,

00:32:45.536 --> 00:32:48.456
listen to side B, never say a word.

00:32:48.496 --> 00:32:52.656
And then get up and go do stuff.
And we did that all the time.

00:32:52.696 --> 00:32:57.576
- And so the first time you impressed your
dad was with the Joe Pass song, right?

00:32:57.596 --> 00:33:01.496
And by the way, we'll have to go to
this song 'cause people must have

00:33:01.556 --> 00:33:05.336
forgot 'cause right? People just think

00:33:05.396 --> 00:33:09.016
you're like a good
communicator or something.

00:33:09.036 --> 00:33:12.736
They don't realize how good you
are at guitar, how good you are at

00:33:13.116 --> 00:33:17.096
actually a lot of instruments, but
guitar especially. And there's this

00:33:17.176 --> 00:33:21.216
video. The greatest guitar solo, period.

00:33:22.296 --> 00:33:25.496
Can you give me some
context for this particular

00:33:26.116 --> 00:33:29.296
intricate, complicated
solo? Who's Joe Pass?

00:33:29.336 --> 00:33:36.696
- Joe Pass was a guitarist. He lived from
1929 to 1994. And he was one of the

00:33:36.736 --> 00:33:40.356
greatest bebop players and solo guitar

00:33:40.396 --> 00:33:44.036
players. So he made a record that
this is off of called Virtuoso in

00:33:44.056 --> 00:33:47.696
1973 that my dad gave me for Christmas

00:33:47.996 --> 00:33:51.896
when I was in 10th grade. And he said ...
And this is not like my dad. My dad worked

00:33:51.936 --> 00:33:55.295
for the railroad. He was
very, you know, few words

00:33:55.576 --> 00:33:59.516
spoken. Born in 1919. He said, "If
you ever learn to play guitar like

00:33:59.576 --> 00:34:01.916
this, you've accomplished
something with your life."

00:34:02.736 --> 00:34:06.235
And I was like, "What?" So
this let, record stay, was

00:34:06.336 --> 00:34:10.276
unopened until about March after Christmas.
And one day I was like, "Okay, I'll

00:34:10.296 --> 00:34:12.516
open it up." And I put it
on, I start listening to it.

00:34:13.956 --> 00:34:17.176
And I was like, "Whoa,
this is kinda cool."

00:34:17.276 --> 00:34:22.256
And so I said, "I think I can figure out
some of this stuff." So I figured out

00:34:23.316 --> 00:34:24.216
this thing.

00:34:24.256 --> 00:34:25.545
- Is it by ear mostly?

00:34:25.556 --> 00:34:28.236
- Yeah, just by ear. I didn't know
any of the chords or anything.

00:34:28.296 --> 00:34:29.856
- If you can listen to a little bit here.

00:34:29.876 --> 00:34:33.756
- If you go back to that Brother to Brother,
Gino Vannelli thing with Carlos Rios

00:34:33.836 --> 00:34:37.726
playing, that stuff is incredibly hard. This,
I'm starting, I don't know any of these chords.

00:34:37.735 --> 00:34:41.636
So I start out ... I don't even know what
that chord is, but I figured it out. I

00:34:41.716 --> 00:34:46.446
I just, and it's weird. I
mean, look at that weird bar.

00:34:46.476 --> 00:34:51.356
- So you're just finding like, playing
around with the, putting your fingers-

00:34:51.376 --> 00:34:51.386
- Yes

00:34:51.386 --> 00:34:52.736
- ... on the various positions.

00:34:52.796 --> 00:34:56.456
- Right, but trying every combination of fingers. I
had never played that chord. That's a weird-looking

00:34:56.496 --> 00:35:01.666
chord. And, but I kept ... I
moved my fingers around till I

00:35:01.696 --> 00:35:04.166
heard to where it sounded like,
"Oh, that's it, definitely."

00:35:04.166 --> 00:35:08.276
And I just looked at my hands like,
"What is that?" Had no idea what it was.

00:35:08.336 --> 00:35:12.696
- So you were connected to the... you
were really connected to the music.

00:35:12.706 --> 00:35:16.696
The... And so that, that's why you can hear...
It's not necessarily... Did you even, you

00:35:16.736 --> 00:35:17.666
didn't have perfect pitch.

00:35:17.676 --> 00:35:17.876
- No.

00:35:17.916 --> 00:35:20.076
- You, and not even relative pitch.

00:35:20.156 --> 00:35:21.316
- No, I did not.

00:35:21.356 --> 00:35:24.806
No, I didn't know anything about intervals. I
didn't know anything about music theory, anything.

00:35:24.816 --> 00:35:25.496
This is all just-

00:35:25.656 --> 00:35:26.406
- Yeah. You're just like playing-

00:35:26.436 --> 00:35:26.476
- Ear

00:35:26.486 --> 00:35:27.896
- ... around with different
shapes. That's amazing.

00:35:27.916 --> 00:35:31.876
- That's right. I mean, look at that weird
bar there. . But then you get into these

00:35:31.916 --> 00:35:47.185
thing. So that stuff there, I
could figure out And then this.

00:35:48.316 --> 00:35:50.666
That stuff I could figure
out. And then these things

00:35:50.716 --> 00:35:57.796
here. Those are just inversions
of an— But I didn't know that.

00:35:57.876 --> 00:36:01.856
I had heard Joe play that on the record. This is the last
song on there. I'd listened to it a bunch of times and

00:36:01.896 --> 00:36:02.166
I started-

00:36:02.196 --> 00:36:06.006
- So you just replay over and over and
over and over, and you're, like, trying

00:36:06.056 --> 00:36:07.196
to replicate it.

00:36:07.216 --> 00:36:11.086
- Yes. And I'm memorizing every different
chord shape. All the chord shapes that I

00:36:11.116 --> 00:36:12.786
had never played before.

00:36:12.786 --> 00:36:16.906
- Would you recommend people do something
like that on a really complicated song?

00:36:16.976 --> 00:36:20.926
- Yeah, but there are so many YouTube videos that
you can go and just learn it without having

00:36:20.936 --> 00:36:24.124
to— Yes. Yeah, I would recommend.

00:36:24.184 --> 00:36:25.604
- I feel like the struggle-

00:36:25.664 --> 00:36:26.824
- The struggle is where it's at.

00:36:26.904 --> 00:36:30.464
- ... this is true for education in general.
People... Like, there's all these

00:36:30.524 --> 00:36:33.474
educators that try to make learning easier

00:36:34.924 --> 00:36:38.564
and more fun, and all that kind
of stuff. Great, wonderful,

00:36:38.604 --> 00:36:41.254
but part of the thing is the struggle.

00:36:41.344 --> 00:36:42.264
- Absolutely.

00:36:42.284 --> 00:36:43.064
- But yeah, let's—

00:36:43.144 --> 00:36:44.774
- I'm sorry, hearing there's.

00:36:44.784 --> 00:36:47.444
- Let's... You're nuts.

00:36:49.924 --> 00:36:55.704
- I heard licks like that all over this,
so I knew that that was and then

00:36:57.724 --> 00:37:04.344
these licks here, he plays a lot of
ideas like that. That's basically a C9

00:37:04.384 --> 00:37:07.414
chord in the top notes of it.

00:37:09.584 --> 00:37:13.553
So all these are just inversions
of the same chord. So if I could

00:37:13.564 --> 00:37:21.384
play that, then it's just figuring
out the single notes, okay? So...

00:37:31.504 --> 00:37:34.904
Okay, so if you just take this
first part here when he goes

00:37:36.524 --> 00:37:38.114
So this, this intro part is...

00:37:38.124 --> 00:37:41.954
- You make it sound so simple when you break it
down. And, and by the way, Joe Pass, incredible

00:37:42.004 --> 00:37:45.904
guitar player. Like, this is obvious.

00:37:45.914 --> 00:37:48.064
- And he improvised all this. He
could have played it like this.

00:37:48.104 --> 00:37:54.634
- But, you know, the first was the
individual notes. Look at that.

00:37:54.634 --> 00:38:03.944
- Ooh, that's hard. Maybe just play it
like that. That sounds more realistic.

00:38:08.224 --> 00:38:13.964
- The amount of different genres that you're
able to replicate is just incredible.

00:38:14.044 --> 00:38:17.824
- This is just taking the needle, moving
it there, then going back a little, oh,

00:38:17.964 --> 00:38:21.944
there. And then by the end,
the record was so scratched.

00:38:24.524 --> 00:38:29.024
It was, but it was worth it.
When I played it for my dad-

00:38:29.344 --> 00:38:32.893
... he couldn't believe. I mean, he didn't
say, "That's amazing." He was just like,

00:38:32.893 --> 00:38:34.994
"Hmm, pretty good."

00:38:35.024 --> 00:38:38.944
- So what was the role of bebop jazz in
the history of music? It seems like

00:38:38.984 --> 00:38:42.924
it was influential in your life.
Another guy you had an incredible

00:38:42.984 --> 00:38:46.904
interview with Flea. People should go
listen to that. Was a great conversation.

00:38:46.964 --> 00:38:50.704
One of the things that surprised me is
just how many musical genres influenced

00:38:50.724 --> 00:38:55.234
Flea. And the guy showed up in
a Miles Davis T-shirt. And-

00:38:55.464 --> 00:38:56.093
- Bebop.

00:38:56.124 --> 00:38:56.564
- And -

00:38:56.584 --> 00:38:58.684
- Miles Davis played with Charlie Parker-

00:38:59.104 --> 00:39:02.444
... when he was 18 years old. And that's...
He was... Charlie Parker was really his

00:39:02.544 --> 00:39:03.524
mentor.

00:39:03.584 --> 00:39:08.373
- Can you explain to me why, with many
of the folks you've interviewed

00:39:09.264 --> 00:39:12.834
and in general out there, in the world of

00:39:12.944 --> 00:39:17.124
jazz, all roads lead to Miles Davis?
Why he's such an influential figure?

00:39:17.164 --> 00:39:19.974
- Because he was the greatest
innovator in the history of

00:39:20.044 --> 00:39:23.584
jazz. He was at the forefront
of all these different

00:39:23.744 --> 00:39:27.584
styles of jazz. I mean, he started
as a bebop player, and then

00:39:27.644 --> 00:39:34.964
he, he had records like the Birth of
Cool, and modal jazz, and hard bop,

00:39:35.024 --> 00:39:38.914
and records like Bitches Brew,
where he started to, I guess you

00:39:38.924 --> 00:39:42.854
would call fusion. You start
to get these records. You

00:39:42.884 --> 00:39:46.174
had two main groups of Miles
Davis. You had the Miles Davis

00:39:46.174 --> 00:39:50.624
'50s quintet and the
Miles Davis '60s quintet.

00:39:50.684 --> 00:39:54.644
Now, Miles made records with many people,
but the '50s quintet had John Coltrane

00:39:54.684 --> 00:39:58.404
in it. Had, I mean, had different piano
players. Could... Wynton Kelly, but Paul

00:39:58.444 --> 00:40:03.584
Chambers in the bass, Philly Joe Jones
on the drums. And that particular group

00:40:04.544 --> 00:40:12.144
was made just incredibly important records.
And then he had his '60s group, which

00:40:12.204 --> 00:40:15.444
was Herbie Hancock on the
piano, Ron Carter on the

00:40:15.464 --> 00:40:19.264
bass, Tony Williams on the
drums, and Wayne Shorter on the

00:40:19.284 --> 00:40:25.914
saxophone. And they made all these
incredibly important records.

00:40:25.944 --> 00:40:30.324
- I forget who said it in an interview
with you, but they talked about like,

00:40:31.144 --> 00:40:35.124
uh, Miles Davis his music feeling like

00:40:35.824 --> 00:40:39.683
I think toes hanging over the
cliff or something like this.

00:40:39.704 --> 00:40:43.584
Meaning, like, there's always a risk, there's
a danger that you're willing to make,

00:40:44.904 --> 00:40:52.364
to fuck it all up live. And that feeling
is what creates the aliveness of the

00:40:52.724 --> 00:40:56.544
music. Like, can you speak
to that? Just the, the

00:40:56.644 --> 00:40:59.944
creating in the music, the
feeling like you're on the

00:41:00.024 --> 00:41:03.404
edge. Like, you're challenging the

00:41:03.444 --> 00:41:07.084
possibilities of what can happen,
and, and it all can go to shit, and

00:41:07.124 --> 00:41:09.624
because of that, it feels alive.

00:41:09.644 --> 00:41:13.604
- Well, when I interviewed Ron
Carter that played in, in Miles's

00:41:13.624 --> 00:41:21.554
'60s quintet, I asked Ron, 'cause Ron
did records, he played bass on 2,200

00:41:21.644 --> 00:41:25.604
recording, famous records. And
I said, "Did you guys ever

00:41:25.644 --> 00:41:29.134
rehearse with Miles?" "No,
never." I said, "So, you,

00:41:29.324 --> 00:41:32.904
what, what would you do?" He goes, "We'd just
show up at the studio, and he'd have the

00:41:32.984 --> 00:41:37.944
charts, put them on the stand
and we would," "we'd just roll."

00:41:37.964 --> 00:41:40.624
And I said, "Would you
listen to it after?" "No."

00:41:41.904 --> 00:41:45.704
And I said, "Well, what about your, what
about the, the live records that you

00:41:45.744 --> 00:41:49.644
did at, when you'd record at clubs and things
like that?" He goes, "We never knew that we

00:41:49.684 --> 00:41:53.604
were recording." He goes, "Maybe I'd see
a, a microphone, a different kind of

00:41:53.644 --> 00:41:57.584
microphone in my bass amp." He
goes, "Then months later, a record

00:41:57.604 --> 00:42:01.584
would come out and I'd see it, and I was on it,
and I would take it down to the union and say, 'I

00:42:01.684 --> 00:42:05.604
played on this record,' so you get paid
for it." But he said, "We didn't even know

00:42:05.644 --> 00:42:06.964
we were recording."

00:42:07.004 --> 00:42:12.384
So Miles was always about, you know,
don't think about it, just play.

00:42:14.284 --> 00:42:17.674
- That's crazy. That was on purpose.
That was done on purpose.

00:42:17.674 --> 00:42:20.104
Not to, not to do the rehearsals.
Not, none, none of that.

00:42:20.164 --> 00:42:23.244
- Yeah, he wanted people to just feel it,

00:42:24.164 --> 00:42:30.068
play it. Thought is the enemy of
flow, as Vinnie Colaiuta told me.

00:42:30.128 --> 00:42:34.028
- Thought is the enemy of flow.
How do you make sense that Flea,

00:42:34.068 --> 00:42:38.198
the bassist for the Red Hot Chili
Peppers, is influenced by bebop jazz?

00:42:38.408 --> 00:42:42.848
- So his stepfather was a jazz bass player.

00:42:42.928 --> 00:42:46.878
And his... When his parents
got divorced, his...

00:42:46.908 --> 00:42:50.508
He was born in Australia,
and then they moved to New

00:42:50.588 --> 00:42:54.448
York. Then his parents got
divorced, and his mom married his

00:42:54.528 --> 00:42:58.348
stepfather, who was a jazz musician.
And they then used to have jam

00:42:58.427 --> 00:43:02.068
sessions at their place, and Flea

00:43:03.168 --> 00:43:07.008
loved it. It was kind of
like my upbringing with my

00:43:07.068 --> 00:43:14.558
dad, playing jazz all the time. Once it
gets inside you, it's just there. And

00:43:14.608 --> 00:43:19.028
and so he is heavily
influenced by jazz musicians.

00:43:19.048 --> 00:43:22.968
- Yeah, his impression was just hilarious. I mean,
he's a character. His whole physical way of being is

00:43:23.008 --> 00:43:26.788
a character. And his impression of
just upright bass is just fun, fun to

00:43:26.868 --> 00:43:27.808
watch. His whole-

00:43:27.868 --> 00:43:31.768
- His intensity when he picked up
his bass during the interview,

00:43:31.828 --> 00:43:39.588
it... He's an intense guy and funny, and
you know, really um, emotional. And,

00:43:39.648 --> 00:43:43.488
And he picks up his bass, and
there's a fierceness that you

00:43:43.528 --> 00:43:47.418
immediately feel. And he starts,
he talks about how he practices.

00:43:47.428 --> 00:43:50.028
And then when he starts
doing the slapping stuff, he

00:43:50.088 --> 00:43:55.558
gets, he's so into it. And, and I'm just
sitting there going, "Whoa." Like, "Wow."

00:43:55.588 --> 00:43:59.568
- Yeah, he talked about his practicing routine with
you. And one of the things, he's like, "I have to

00:43:59.608 --> 00:44:01.328
practice the slap." And-

00:44:01.348 --> 00:44:04.728
... you know, there's differences in the structure
of the different bands. But usually, like, the

00:44:04.828 --> 00:44:08.068
bassist has a vibe to them.

00:44:08.088 --> 00:44:11.968
I don't know if we can put words to exactly
what that is. There's a kind of energy

00:44:12.848 --> 00:44:14.088
that drives the band.

00:44:14.148 --> 00:44:17.948
- To me, the bass is one of the only
instruments that, when you play a bad

00:44:18.048 --> 00:44:23.728
note, everybody notices. I started
on the bass- ... as a kid.

00:44:23.768 --> 00:44:26.778
- Oh, interesting. But you also
played drums. You also played-

00:44:26.808 --> 00:44:29.578
- Yeah, but my first instrument
was the cello in third grade.

00:44:29.578 --> 00:44:29.608
- Oh.

00:44:29.618 --> 00:44:33.528
- And then I switched to the bass in sixth
grade. And my, I majored, my undergrad

00:44:33.548 --> 00:44:40.268
degree is in classical bass. So I
always think of myself as a bass player

00:44:40.508 --> 00:44:45.597
first. And I always think the bass is
the most important instrument because-

00:44:45.597 --> 00:44:46.408
- Strong words.

00:44:46.418 --> 00:44:50.268
- ... because as much as I love
to play the guitar, and I

00:44:50.308 --> 00:44:53.597
love to play the guitar more than
anything, I think, but the bass really

00:44:53.648 --> 00:44:57.448
defines what the quality of the
chord is. 'Cause you can put the

00:44:57.508 --> 00:45:00.858
root in there. You can put the third of the chord
in the bass. You can put the fifth in there.

00:45:00.888 --> 00:45:04.828
You can play a lot of notes. And whatever
you play in the bass kinda defines what

00:45:04.868 --> 00:45:08.348
kind of chord it is. So, the
bass player has a lot of power.

00:45:08.428 --> 00:45:11.948
- I have to go back to our, the beginning of our
conversation. What do you think are some of the

00:45:12.008 --> 00:45:15.908
great solos of all time? Can we

00:45:16.028 --> 00:45:19.948
put a few into consideration?
You have a great list on top

00:45:20.188 --> 00:45:22.828
20 rock guitar solos of all time.

00:45:22.868 --> 00:45:25.968
- Yeah, so I put Comfortably Numb
as my favorite, as my top one.

00:45:26.008 --> 00:45:27.338
- Yeah, on that day, right?

00:45:27.388 --> 00:45:33.097
- On that day. Right. Now the day later, I
would have said, "It's the second solo."

00:45:34.588 --> 00:45:34.738
- Okay.

00:45:34.748 --> 00:45:38.728
- But I did the first solo because,
because nobody talks about that solo.

00:45:38.748 --> 00:45:41.488
And that solo is equally
great. And when David

00:45:41.508 --> 00:45:45.348
Gilmour... When I played
it for him, and we

00:45:45.368 --> 00:45:47.708
talked about it in my
interview with him, it

00:45:47.788 --> 00:45:51.708
was... Just to watch his
face when he listened to it

00:45:51.788 --> 00:45:55.768
was incredible. I mean, I'm thinking to
myself, it's like, I'm sitting with David

00:45:55.808 --> 00:45:59.388
Gilmour, and he's listening
to Comfortably Numb. And he's

00:45:59.508 --> 00:46:02.548
hearing it. He's played it a million times

00:46:02.628 --> 00:46:07.788
live, but how many times has he gone
back and listened to it on the record?

00:46:07.798 --> 00:46:11.458
Probably not for a long time. And then
he's hearing it, and he's like, "Ooh."

00:46:11.468 --> 00:46:14.408
- Maybe you just don't look back. When you
do great things, you don't look back.

00:46:14.468 --> 00:46:18.308
- Miles never looked back. He never wanted
to hear the old stuff. He always moved on.

00:46:18.348 --> 00:46:22.298
- There was this funny moment
where you made a video

00:46:23.088 --> 00:46:26.708
why David Gilmour will never be on the
channel. And then you ended up, of course,

00:46:26.768 --> 00:46:30.508
interviewing him twice. He's one of
the greatest guitar players of all

00:46:30.548 --> 00:46:33.608
time. What do you think is
at the core of his genius?

00:46:33.668 --> 00:46:39.148
- He has just an incredible
melodic sense. He knows

00:46:40.348 --> 00:46:44.188
how phrases should be put
together. There's a flow to

00:46:44.228 --> 00:46:47.408
his ideas that I think is just
incredible. It's the same with

00:46:47.447 --> 00:46:51.128
Hendrix. This flow, how one idea

00:46:51.228 --> 00:46:56.468
leads to the next, how there's space
between them. It's just like speaking.

00:46:56.488 --> 00:47:02.248
- That's what I read about Miles Davis
is very good at understanding tempo

00:47:03.368 --> 00:47:12.128
and the value of silence. And I think
David Gilmour doesn't always play fast.

00:47:12.148 --> 00:47:15.488
But he does a lot with less.

00:47:15.498 --> 00:47:19.168
And then some of that is also on the
more technical side, probably the tone

00:47:19.568 --> 00:47:26.588
of the... I mean, he's one of the most
uniquely recognizable tones in all of music.

00:47:26.628 --> 00:47:30.728
What do you understand about what it takes
to shape the tone that is David Gilmour?

00:47:30.748 --> 00:47:33.308
- He has a very sophisticated setup-

00:47:33.348 --> 00:47:35.898
... for his tone, and that was one
of the things when I went to his

00:47:35.988 --> 00:47:39.968
studio. And I said to him, "So David, is
there anything I'm not supposed to see

00:47:40.008 --> 00:47:41.988
here?" I mean, he never
sits down and shows-

00:47:41.998 --> 00:47:44.588
... people his gear, and
he laughed about it.

00:47:44.628 --> 00:47:48.498
But there I am, sitting there right
next to all these pedals that ... And

00:47:48.768 --> 00:47:52.348
I, and I asked his tech, Phil, I said,
"These are the same ones you used on the

00:47:52.368 --> 00:47:56.318
records?" He's like, "Yeah." His
tech has been with him for, like, 50

00:47:56.408 --> 00:48:03.328
years. And I mean, the exact ones?
Yes. It's just, it's hard to... It's

00:48:03.348 --> 00:48:07.248
hard to imagine that those things
still... Of course, though.

00:48:07.268 --> 00:48:11.018
They... He's just kept it. Yeah, this
is his Binson Echorec that he played

00:48:11.068 --> 00:48:12.128
through, and this is this.

00:48:13.008 --> 00:48:16.988
You know, these are all the same effects
pedals. And the... Wait, is this

00:48:17.028 --> 00:48:20.868
the same Hiwatt amp? Yeah. Is
this the same... Yes. Yeah, you

00:48:20.928 --> 00:48:23.588
get some new stuff. But they

00:48:24.408 --> 00:48:28.168
keep all their own gear, and that's,
uh ... I mean, he does sell his

00:48:28.188 --> 00:48:31.928
guitars for charity. But, like, he
has a black Strat that is a, it's a

00:48:32.008 --> 00:48:35.428
signature version. It's like
an exact copy of his old one.

00:48:35.488 --> 00:48:39.188
So to him, it sounds exactly
the same, plays the same.

00:48:39.228 --> 00:48:42.542
- Well, of course, they converge
towards that kind of f-...

00:48:42.542 --> 00:48:46.432
hardware. But there's so
many tiny details over

00:48:46.472 --> 00:48:50.232
the years. You see the final
result of it, but there's a

00:48:50.272 --> 00:48:54.202
journey there, of exploring.
And of course, he's not...

00:48:54.292 --> 00:48:56.942
I guess he's not doing any soft...
Like, no emulation, no amp?

00:48:56.952 --> 00:49:00.862
- He does do emulation, actually.
He does. He has this thing,

00:49:00.912 --> 00:49:04.472
this is... I asked him in the first
interview about this. There's a little

00:49:04.552 --> 00:49:08.472
rack thing that I had heard that he used,
but I asked him for sure. It's called the

00:49:08.652 --> 00:49:12.242
Zoom 9030. I put out a
short where he talks about

00:49:12.272 --> 00:49:16.012
it. I said, "So, that,
that Zoom 9030, is that a

00:49:16.092 --> 00:49:19.112
real thing?" 'Cause I've read about it.
He's like, "Yeah." And he talks about

00:49:19.152 --> 00:49:22.032
how, when he's sitting
there recording on his

00:49:22.152 --> 00:49:26.112
own... And he runs Pro Tools
himself, and so he'll be

00:49:26.152 --> 00:49:30.092
sitting there. There's no one there to help him.
He's like, "I'll just plug into this thing, and then

00:49:30.112 --> 00:49:33.992
I'll play a solo with this
model." It's like a kind of

00:49:34.002 --> 00:49:37.172
'90s modeling, early modeling thing.

00:49:37.232 --> 00:49:41.282
And he'll play a solo, and then after a
while, you hear the solo, and it's like,

00:49:42.292 --> 00:49:45.672
"Well, I'm not gonna replay that. That sounds great."
You get used to the sound of it, and that's what it

00:49:45.772 --> 00:49:49.752
is. So people always talked about, "Oh, well, he
couldn't have used that. He's recording through an

00:49:49.852 --> 00:49:52.692
amp," and... 'Cause it sounds great. And,

00:49:52.752 --> 00:49:56.592
And then he's like, "Yeah, yeah, so
that's what I use." And then I have the

00:49:56.612 --> 00:50:00.372
video of it right there, and
it says his presets, DG1 and

00:50:00.392 --> 00:50:02.972
DG2 and, you know, whatever.

00:50:03.012 --> 00:50:06.802
- What's your process for preparing for
interviews like that? You've done a few

00:50:06.872 --> 00:50:08.912
legendary people.

00:50:08.952 --> 00:50:12.672
- I never prepare for interviews, because

00:50:13.772 --> 00:50:17.432
I ask people things that
I'm interested in knowing.

00:50:17.472 --> 00:50:19.932
- So, just letting your
curiosity just pull a-

00:50:19.972 --> 00:50:20.112
- Yes

00:50:20.172 --> 00:50:20.672
- ... pull you forward?

00:50:20.692 --> 00:50:24.412
- And I can think of 100
questions to ask David Gilmour,

00:50:24.472 --> 00:50:28.482
and... But I always ask my questions
based on what they say to me.

00:50:28.512 --> 00:50:32.902
So, but I do make a playlist of
songs that I wanna talk about.

00:50:33.672 --> 00:50:37.532
So, that kind of guides me, is
that... 'Cause I wanna make sure that

00:50:39.072 --> 00:50:46.672
There's specific things that I need to
play to, so that you can jog his memory.

00:50:46.682 --> 00:50:50.312
'Cause anytime you play something that
somebody recorded, even 50 years ago, they'll

00:50:50.392 --> 00:50:57.041
remember. If they don't remember
the exact specifics, that,

00:50:57.041 --> 00:50:59.872
that brings it to life to them again.

00:50:59.912 --> 00:51:03.442
And they can, they can kind
of piece together some

00:51:03.512 --> 00:51:07.432
aspects about it, and they
can really talk. He can talk

00:51:07.472 --> 00:51:11.402
about the phrasing and the, you
know, the kind of melodic direction

00:51:11.432 --> 00:51:12.582
of things like that.

00:51:12.612 --> 00:51:16.452
- So, there's a lot of tiny details that go
into a particular song, whether it's in the

00:51:16.532 --> 00:51:19.512
production or how it's played or how
it was composed, all that kind of

00:51:19.552 --> 00:51:22.772
stuff. And you don't know
what those are ahead of time.

00:51:22.832 --> 00:51:23.012
- No.

00:51:23.052 --> 00:51:26.572
- You just know the song, and you just
are looking to jog their memory,

00:51:27.412 --> 00:51:31.092
and maybe your own curiosity of like, "How
did you do this?" Or, "How do, what, this

00:51:31.172 --> 00:51:35.032
sound or that?" You make it look easy, but

00:51:35.152 --> 00:51:39.112
you have to have a depth of knowledge.
You're saying you don't prepare.

00:51:39.212 --> 00:51:41.732
- I have an incredibly good memory.

00:51:41.792 --> 00:51:41.981
- Exactly.

00:51:41.992 --> 00:51:45.832
- That's what it is. It's that I
can remember when records came

00:51:45.932 --> 00:51:48.731
out, who produced them, where
they recorded them, who was the

00:51:48.772 --> 00:51:52.272
engineer, what songs are on it.

00:51:52.352 --> 00:51:56.292
And not only that, but the people
I'm interviewing know that I

00:51:56.332 --> 00:51:58.312
can play all the parts-

00:51:58.752 --> 00:52:02.532
... of all the instruments, 'cause I've done
breakdowns of their songs, which is why I get the

00:52:02.572 --> 00:52:06.152
interviews with them in
the first place, really.

00:52:06.172 --> 00:52:09.522
- But the actual, like, the skill of
the interview, the thing you're not

00:52:09.572 --> 00:52:14.252
saying, the preparation, is the
you young listening to bebop.

00:52:14.272 --> 00:52:14.562
- That's right.

00:52:14.562 --> 00:52:17.652
- It's the, it's the background
knowledge, it's the soul

00:52:18.232 --> 00:52:24.372
carrying with you, being able to
radiate the love of the soul of music.

00:52:25.072 --> 00:52:28.332
- I will say this, Lex, is
that the other thing is that

00:52:29.332 --> 00:52:32.562
most of these people have a
really good sense of humor.

00:52:32.592 --> 00:52:36.512
When I was, when... The first time I
interviewed David in New York, my brother

00:52:36.552 --> 00:52:40.402
John came along, and he is a
massive David Gilmour fan.

00:52:40.432 --> 00:52:44.092
That's his biggest influence
as a guitar player. And so he

00:52:44.192 --> 00:52:47.672
said, "You're interviewing David Gilmour? Oh,
I'm coming." I was like, "All right. Come on.

00:52:47.692 --> 00:52:50.952
Come on down." So, so my brother
John's standing about five feet

00:52:50.992 --> 00:52:54.892
away. And John is a sales guy, but
he... Great guitar player. So John's

00:52:54.932 --> 00:52:57.981
like... I was like, "This is John... This
is... David, this is my brother, John."

00:52:58.792 --> 00:53:02.662
"David, great to meet you, buddy." And you
know, it sounds like it's so... He's a sales

00:53:02.712 --> 00:53:06.472
guy. And, and so during the
interview, I said, I was like,

00:53:07.252 --> 00:53:10.692
"Hey, John, what was I gonna ask David? Oh, ask
him about the Gilmour effect." "Oh, yeah, that's

00:53:10.812 --> 00:53:14.672
right." And the Gilmour effect is my
thing that I say in the comments section

00:53:14.712 --> 00:53:17.592
when people say... Anytime
anybody plays anything

00:53:17.692 --> 00:53:25.532
technical, "Oh, yeah, that's great, but
I much prefer David Gilmour." And so I

00:53:25.572 --> 00:53:28.552
always call it the Gilmour effect.
Anytime I have, like, Yngwie Malmsteen-

00:53:28.572 --> 00:53:28.582
- Mm, yeah.

00:53:28.612 --> 00:53:30.872
- Anybody that played,
that has chops that I—

00:53:30.892 --> 00:53:36.052
... interview, the negative comments are
always, "Well, I prefer David Gilmour."

00:53:36.132 --> 00:53:36.542
- Yeah, yeah.

00:53:36.552 --> 00:53:40.372
- And I said that, I told David that. He's
like, "Well, maybe they should keep their

00:53:40.472 --> 00:53:43.982
opinions to themselves."

00:53:43.992 --> 00:53:47.852
- Yeah, a lot of these folks have really wonderful
personalities, with a, with a trusted person

00:53:47.892 --> 00:53:51.652
to be able to reveal that personality.
So, Comfortably Numb at the top on that

00:53:51.722 --> 00:53:53.652
day. What else is up there?

00:53:53.662 --> 00:53:56.542
- Stairway to Heaven. Hey, Joe.

00:53:56.592 --> 00:54:01.502
- But in that list, your top
Hendrix solo is Hey, Joe?

00:54:01.532 --> 00:54:04.992
- It's the first guitar solo I ever learned,
so I had to put it on there. So, I don't,

00:54:05.052 --> 00:54:08.952
necessarily do these by...
I do those in kind of how

00:54:09.012 --> 00:54:11.882
important they are to
me and my development.

00:54:11.912 --> 00:54:15.692
So, there's always a
biographical component to these

00:54:15.752 --> 00:54:19.552
lists. Number three was Kid
Charlemagne, a Steely Dan solo—

00:54:19.672 --> 00:54:25.852
Larry Carlton. Amazing solo,
extremely difficult to figure out.

00:54:25.892 --> 00:54:29.182
Probably, there's two solos
on the list that are just

00:54:29.272 --> 00:54:33.192
about, are very... That one I can play.

00:54:33.532 --> 00:54:37.452
But there's a few solos that are very hard
to play. Stone in Love by Journey, by Neal

00:54:37.532 --> 00:54:41.602
Neal Schon, is very hard
to play some licks. Um,

00:54:42.812 --> 00:54:46.696
the, um—There's a song... There's
a solo by a guitarist, Carlos

00:54:46.796 --> 00:54:50.586
Rios, that people don't know. It's Brother
to Brother, a Gino Vannelli song, but it's

00:54:51.556 --> 00:54:54.906
extremely hard to play and figure out. And

00:54:55.476 --> 00:54:59.406
that people don't know the solos. I put it on my list
'cause I knew that a lot of people were gonna watch it and

00:54:59.416 --> 00:55:00.906
they're gonna know what this solo is.

00:55:01.236 --> 00:55:04.816
- For me, the sentimental one, my, my
first solo is Mr. Crowley, Randy

00:55:04.896 --> 00:55:08.456
Rhoads. I like the musicality
of Mr. Crowley, that there is a

00:55:08.496 --> 00:55:12.056
melodic component to it. You're playing
really fast, but there's a melody to

00:55:12.076 --> 00:55:15.896
it. And also, there's like
a legendary nature to the,

00:55:15.936 --> 00:55:20.095
the brief time we had Randy Rhoads.

00:55:20.136 --> 00:55:20.146
- Yes.

00:55:20.156 --> 00:55:23.416
- It's probably one of the
greatest guitarists ever.

00:55:23.426 --> 00:55:31.456
- '56 to '82, I think. Terrible.
Um, he was an absolute

00:55:31.536 --> 00:55:34.476
brilliant guitarist, had his own style.

00:55:34.496 --> 00:55:37.536
- We should say he's the guitarist
for Ozzy Osbourne, the band.

00:55:37.576 --> 00:55:43.296
- Yeah. And that Mr. Crowley solo
is a great solo, great solo. And,

00:55:44.536 --> 00:55:52.346
He's incredibly influential as a guitar
player too, for metal guitar players and,

00:55:52.436 --> 00:55:54.096
um, I love Randy Rhoads.

00:55:54.216 --> 00:56:00.176
- Uh, another guy, so one of my
favorites is Mark Knopfler.

00:56:00.196 --> 00:56:03.816
- Yes. And I did have Mark Knopfler
on my list, Sultans of Swing.

00:56:03.856 --> 00:56:04.466
- That's right, you did have-

00:56:04.476 --> 00:56:07.456
- Now, I had it high on the
list, and I'll tell you why.

00:56:07.516 --> 00:56:11.076
I would've had it lower 'cause it's one of the
early ones, 'cause I wanted people to be like,

00:56:11.096 --> 00:56:14.186
"Okay, oh, this is a serious list."

00:56:14.996 --> 00:56:18.576
So Rick's gonna talk about
serious stuff. So, um-

00:56:18.586 --> 00:56:24.256
And Rick's gonna play along
with all these things.

00:56:32.046 --> 00:56:35.876
So I wanted to kind of state that at the
beginning of the video. I mean, I made the

00:56:35.916 --> 00:56:39.756
video in one day to do 20 solos. I think
I played 19 of them, but the Heart

00:56:39.876 --> 00:56:41.286
solo that I had on there-

00:56:41.716 --> 00:56:45.416
... Nancy Wilson, I played the
video of. And I tried to get

00:56:46.276 --> 00:56:50.776
a couple of my friends to play the
Ice Cream Man, Van Halen solo.

00:56:50.796 --> 00:56:51.146
- Yeah, it was just-

00:56:51.156 --> 00:56:55.055
- So I called Dweezil Zappa, and I was like,
"Dweezil, can you play the Ice Cream Man

00:56:55.076 --> 00:56:58.946
solo? I'm making a video about it." He's
like, "Oh, I'd have to practice that." Then I

00:56:58.976 --> 00:57:02.836
called my friend Phil X who's an amazing
guitar player, and he's like, "No, I'd have to

00:57:02.856 --> 00:57:06.536
practice that." I was like, "Come on, man,
can't let me play Ice Cream Man?" The

00:57:06.616 --> 00:57:10.496
opening lick of Ice Cream Man that
he plays is very hard to play 'cause

00:57:10.536 --> 00:57:13.336
it's an incredibly long stretch.

00:57:13.405 --> 00:57:17.136
And it hurt my fingers to do, and
Eddie would turn his guitar up like

00:57:17.236 --> 00:57:23.596
this to play. And plus, it's a tricky...
It just... It's a tricky rhythm,

00:57:24.276 --> 00:57:28.436
and, and it's such a big stretch. It's
like, "Man, I can't... That hurts my hand."

00:57:28.516 --> 00:57:34.236
- I just love that that's the Van
Halen solo you have. The top 20.

00:57:34.256 --> 00:57:35.656
- See, I have to do some-

00:57:35.736 --> 00:57:36.196
- Yeah, yeah, yeah

00:57:36.356 --> 00:57:38.936
- ... There's so many Van Halen. My God,
it could be... There... I could pick

00:57:40.356 --> 00:57:42.536
25 different Van Halen solos.

00:57:42.556 --> 00:57:46.236
- But to me, I mean, there
really is nobody like

00:57:46.496 --> 00:57:50.356
Mark Knopfler. I mean, his is unique
guitars. There's something about his

00:57:50.416 --> 00:57:58.016
tone. Speaking of Gilmour,
there's just the tone, the care,

00:57:58.036 --> 00:58:00.436
the timing of the notes.

00:58:00.456 --> 00:58:04.156
His improvisation, like the live
performances of Sultans of Swing that's been

00:58:04.176 --> 00:58:11.756
actually going like somewhat viral
around recently, his pretty old

00:58:11.836 --> 00:58:18.256
live performance of Sultans of Swing.
For me, Brothers in Arms, these kind of-

00:58:19.176 --> 00:58:19.185
- Great

00:58:19.185 --> 00:58:21.456
- ... soulful, mournful type of

00:58:22.636 --> 00:58:26.436
solos, he does really, really well.
Also, the interesting instrumentation

00:58:26.476 --> 00:58:31.556
of Romeo and Juliet. Just so many...
Just... Truly one of the greats.

00:58:31.616 --> 00:58:34.746
- Now, obviously the intro to
Money for Nothing is one of the

00:58:34.856 --> 00:58:38.666
greatest. Almost impossible to recreate

00:58:38.916 --> 00:58:42.905
that because of the sound
is so unique and his...

00:58:42.956 --> 00:58:46.036
It's just improvised. It's so cool.

00:58:46.116 --> 00:58:52.316
- Yeah. There's certain songs like Europa by
Santana, Santana can have that tone too.

00:58:52.376 --> 00:58:55.596
That Mark Knopfler makes
me real- just how clean it

00:58:55.676 --> 00:59:00.535
is. I think he beats B.B. King in my
book in terms of the cleanness of just

00:59:01.456 --> 00:59:05.276
pure beauty of a single note.
It's like a power of a single

00:59:05.356 --> 00:59:09.396
note. I don't know anybody
who beats Mark Knopfler.

00:59:09.436 --> 00:59:15.256
- Well, that thing about being able to
recognize somebody from a note. You know?

00:59:15.276 --> 00:59:15.466
- Yeah, that's-

00:59:15.536 --> 00:59:19.466
- When I hear Brian May, I can
immediately recognize it's Brian May.

00:59:19.516 --> 00:59:23.196
Incredibly melodic, the
tone that he has. Gilmour,

00:59:23.256 --> 00:59:28.376
Hendrix, everyone that we're talking about,
Van Halen. It's just, they have that

00:59:29.576 --> 00:59:32.286
one note. It's like, "Oh,
I know who that is." And

00:59:32.336 --> 00:59:35.076
that's, that's why we're
talking about him.

00:59:35.096 --> 00:59:36.836
- That'd be funny. That'd be a good video-

00:59:36.856 --> 00:59:38.536
- B.B. King, you hear one note

00:59:38.756 --> 00:59:44.736
- ... as a test of like how quickly can you
recognize just a solo starts playing-

00:59:44.776 --> 00:59:46.776
- That's a great... I'm
gonna make that video-

00:59:46.796 --> 00:59:46.806
- ... one note

00:59:46.806 --> 00:59:49.186
- ... tomorrow. Lex, you'll-

00:59:49.196 --> 00:59:49.476
- I don't know.

00:59:49.496 --> 00:59:51.356
- The day after tomorrow, you'll see it.

00:59:52.076 --> 00:59:52.926
- I would love to see that.

00:59:52.926 --> 00:59:55.636
- Can you say, can you recognize
these players by one note?

00:59:55.656 --> 00:59:56.696
- By one note.

00:59:56.736 --> 01:00:00.476
I think it's... I think we're being a little
too aggressive with that. I think you

01:00:00.516 --> 01:00:01.826
need like two or three or four-

01:00:01.876 --> 01:00:02.216
- No, no, no, no

01:00:02.256 --> 01:00:02.626
- ... or five notes.

01:00:02.626 --> 01:00:06.056
- I guarantee you. So I was gonna do
a video last week where I was gonna

01:00:06.096 --> 01:00:09.666
play songs in reverse, okay?

01:00:09.736 --> 01:00:13.266
See if you can recognize these songs in
reverse. And I had my two assistants come in.

01:00:13.266 --> 01:00:16.736
It's like, "Do you know what song that is?"
They're like, "Oh, that's Adele." Like,

01:00:16.746 --> 01:00:20.586
"What?" Then they're like, "Oh,
that's, that's Nirvana." Instantly,

01:00:20.616 --> 01:00:23.776
they could recognize. Like, "Well, that's not
worth me." It's like, yeah, it's so obvious.

01:00:23.856 --> 01:00:27.176
You hear the tone of the voice backwards,
forwards, it doesn't matter. You know who it is.

01:00:27.416 --> 01:00:30.016
- Oh, interesting. Okay.
So it's about the tone.

01:00:30.056 --> 01:00:35.896
How could you possibly know the... from a
single note? I guess Van Halen, you can.

01:00:35.956 --> 01:00:39.696
- One note of, of B.B. King's
vibrato, you could know.

01:00:41.076 --> 01:00:44.856
I'm gonna... What I'll do is I
would separate the guitars. I can

01:00:44.916 --> 01:00:47.666
actually separate the tracks,
and I'll just play one note.

01:00:47.696 --> 01:00:50.486
- You think you could, from a single
vibrato, you can know it's B.B. King?

01:00:50.496 --> 01:00:53.240
- Yes. Well, we'll see.

01:00:53.260 --> 01:00:54.660
- Put it on record, I'm skeptical.

01:00:54.720 --> 01:00:58.620
- I'm gonna do, I'll do twenty of them.
Can you recognize these guitarists from

01:00:58.660 --> 01:00:59.580
a single note?

01:00:59.620 --> 01:01:01.280
- Could you recognize Stevie Ray Vaughan-

01:01:01.350 --> 01:01:01.610
- Absolutely

01:01:01.610 --> 01:01:11.260
- ... versus Eric Clapton? All right. You
