01:01:56.030 --> 01:01:59.940
... and what it represents, so
in that sense, Tears in Heaven.

01:01:59.960 --> 01:02:03.230
- Well, the story behind
that is heartbreaking.

01:02:03.260 --> 01:02:07.980
- And then, I personally really love
the sound of Wonderful Tonight.

01:02:08.020 --> 01:02:11.280
- That's a great song. That's one
of my favorite Clapton songs.

01:02:11.300 --> 01:02:13.510
- And I, as I was, like, listening to it,

01:02:14.900 --> 01:02:18.660
just doing a whole personal
journey introspection,

01:02:18.720 --> 01:02:20.520
knowing that I'm gonna talk to Rick Beato,

01:02:21.440 --> 01:02:24.300
listening to just a bunch of songs, and I

01:02:24.420 --> 01:02:28.220
learned, it's embarrassing
that I didn't know the

01:02:28.500 --> 01:02:32.160
stories behind the music,
but I learned that Eric

01:02:32.180 --> 01:02:34.840
Clapton was married for 10, for a decade

01:02:36.020 --> 01:02:39.630
to the same woman that George
Harrison was married to.

01:02:39.630 --> 01:02:44.560
And that this woman was
the muse, the inspiration

01:02:45.200 --> 01:02:51.710
for, like, so many of the
legendary songs of rock-

01:02:51.710 --> 01:02:55.620
... including Wonderful
Tonight, including Layla-

01:02:55.780 --> 01:02:58.720
... and including George
Harrison's Something.

01:02:59.000 --> 01:03:04.330
Legendary song also. The same woman. Is
she the greatest muse in rock history?

01:03:04.500 --> 01:03:05.600
- Probably, yes.

01:03:05.660 --> 01:03:11.320
- This is great. So in your interviews
of musicians and producers,

01:03:12.660 --> 01:03:16.540
I think the thing you're ultimately
fascinated by is their whole, the

01:03:16.580 --> 01:03:20.260
process, the recording,
the production, the

01:03:20.320 --> 01:03:23.870
songwriting, the different
elements of the process. So,

01:03:24.000 --> 01:03:27.940
Are there examples of different
things that stand out to you

01:03:28.780 --> 01:03:32.530
from the all the interviews you've
done? And all by the way, all

01:03:32.560 --> 01:03:36.480
the recording and production you've done
yourself. So on the recording front,

01:03:36.500 --> 01:03:40.289
on the production front, on the
songwriting process front, just things

01:03:40.340 --> 01:03:42.470
that pop into memory.

01:03:42.520 --> 01:03:46.420
- When I've interviewed the guys
that are the producers, like Rick

01:03:46.460 --> 01:03:50.360
Rubin, Daniel Lanois, Brendan
O'Brien, Butch Vig, the thing

01:03:50.400 --> 01:03:54.360
about producers, as opposed to people
that are musicians, if you're a in a

01:03:54.400 --> 01:03:58.320
musician, even if you're David
Gilmour, you do a record, and then you

01:03:58.360 --> 01:04:01.610
tour, and then you do another
record, maybe years go by, but

01:04:01.640 --> 01:04:05.600
producers are working on multiple records,

01:04:05.980 --> 01:04:09.520
you know, sometimes at a time.
Rick Rubin could be working on

01:04:09.660 --> 01:04:13.550
multiple records, and
the variety of things

01:04:13.600 --> 01:04:16.820
that they do, you can talk to.
I mean, I can talk to Rick

01:04:16.920 --> 01:04:20.800
about the Chili Peppers. I
can talk to him about Johnny

01:04:20.860 --> 01:04:24.640
Cash. I can talk to him about
Tom Petty, and all these

01:04:24.680 --> 01:04:28.600
records that I love, and there's
just so many interesting stories

01:04:28.720 --> 01:04:32.500
that ... I mean, these interviews
could go on for, for days

01:04:32.580 --> 01:04:39.880
with Rick, and the variety of records
that he worked on. And there's so

01:04:40.060 --> 01:04:44.030
much knowledge to be gained,
for me at least, and

01:04:44.160 --> 01:04:47.860
I think that the craft of production and

01:04:47.960 --> 01:04:55.000
recording engineering is something that
is not well-documented. Especially

01:04:55.060 --> 01:04:58.940
since there's so few
studios nowadays, where

01:04:58.960 --> 01:05:03.220
there used to be a mentorship thing, where you'd
go and you'd work as an assistant engineer.

01:05:03.260 --> 01:05:07.140
And you'd work your way up. I interviewed
a guy named Ken Scott that worked with the

01:05:07.160 --> 01:05:10.680
Beatles. I interviewed him at Abbey
Road Studios, it's just two months

01:05:10.740 --> 01:05:18.120
ago, and he started as a tape op when he
was 16. He started on the Hard Day's Night

01:05:18.200 --> 01:05:22.180
record with the Beatles, and he worked
his way up, and he said the first time he

01:05:22.220 --> 01:05:26.880
ever recorded an orchestra was he recorded
I Am the Walrus, the orchestra part.

01:05:26.920 --> 01:05:30.710
He set up the mics, and I asked him, I said,
"So where was the band?" "Standing right

01:05:30.720 --> 01:05:34.610
behind me." The Beatles, right behind
him. The guy I'm interviewing at Abbey

01:05:34.700 --> 01:05:42.200
Road recorded I Am the Walrus there. I
mean, he recorded many Beatles songs, and,

01:05:42.600 --> 01:05:46.340
and he was 18 years old, and the ...
I mean, I just can't, I can't even

01:05:46.880 --> 01:05:49.970
fathom that. We ... They have a little
cafe in the basement of Abbey Road, and I

01:05:50.000 --> 01:05:53.690
said, "Did the Beatles come in here?" He goes,
"Oh, yeah, they come in here and get coffee,"

01:05:53.720 --> 01:05:56.550
and I remember when they
got two microwaves that

01:05:57.360 --> 01:06:01.100
like the first microwaves in 1965,
and they were amazed by them, and,

01:06:01.180 --> 01:06:04.700
It's hard to imagine that
I'm talking to people

01:06:04.820 --> 01:06:08.610
that worked on these
historic records. But, you

01:06:08.660 --> 01:06:11.740
know, they all start with a
blank tape or an empty hard

01:06:11.780 --> 01:06:15.720
drive, and then, you've eventually

01:06:15.740 --> 01:06:19.240
filled them up with this music
that you can't, you can never

01:06:19.300 --> 01:06:24.140
imagine it not existing, like Stairway
to Heaven, or whatever it is.

01:06:25.000 --> 01:06:28.900
- It's funny, like, looking back, even
probably for them, just to realize they've

01:06:28.940 --> 01:06:31.460
created that magic is hard to believe.

01:06:31.480 --> 01:06:35.830
'Cause you're looking at a blank thing and
then magic comes out, and you don't even,

01:06:36.720 --> 01:06:40.420
you don't even understand. I you don't
understand, probably a lot of these

01:06:40.460 --> 01:06:45.720
artists don't understand where that came
from. They're channeling some deeper thing.

01:06:45.740 --> 01:06:49.160
- When I interviewed Brian May, he told
me, I can't even remember if this

01:06:49.240 --> 01:06:52.860
was, if we talked about it on
camera or not, but we talked about

01:06:52.940 --> 01:06:56.636
Bohemian Rhapsody, and at
the very end...There was a

01:06:56.876 --> 01:07:00.776
thing where he was depressing his
whammy bar a little bit, and it

01:07:00.916 --> 01:07:04.876
sounds like the piano is out of tune. I
never noticed it before. He mentioned

01:07:04.916 --> 01:07:11.496
this to me. And he said it always bothered
him. And there's always something

01:07:11.556 --> 01:07:16.186
about these songs that bothers
people. Even these songs that he-

01:07:16.186 --> 01:07:17.056
- These old things, yeah.

01:07:17.116 --> 01:07:18.476
- Right. There's always little things-

01:07:18.486 --> 01:07:22.436
... and they sit and they hear it, and they're
like, "Oh, man. I wish I'd been up a little higher

01:07:22.476 --> 01:07:23.716
on that," or whatever.

01:07:23.756 --> 01:07:29.096
- I mean, that... there's certain
moments in songs that are just

01:07:30.176 --> 01:07:34.136
unlike anything else. In Bohemian
Rhapsody when Freddie Mercury is,

01:07:34.716 --> 01:07:38.636
"Sometimes wish I'd
never been born at all."

01:07:38.696 --> 01:07:42.896
And then guitar comes in. I mean,
there's just nothing like that.

01:07:42.916 --> 01:07:46.496
That was... That... I don't
even know. I mean, that whole

01:07:46.576 --> 01:07:50.196
thing, you've done videos on it.
It's an incredibly complicated

01:07:50.296 --> 01:07:54.176
composition. It's crazy that
a popular song, popular

01:07:54.216 --> 01:07:57.096
rock song could be this operatic, so

01:07:57.196 --> 01:08:00.776
complicated. The other thing
akin to that moment is,

01:08:00.856 --> 01:08:08.766
Phil Collins with In the Air Tonight, the
drum bridge. Do do do do do do do do.

01:08:08.766 --> 01:08:14.906
Yeah. What is that? I don't
understand how you can create

01:08:14.906 --> 01:08:18.836
that. What is that? Why
is that so magical? Why

01:08:18.876 --> 01:08:22.716
is that so singular inside
a particular song and in

01:08:22.816 --> 01:08:26.756
rock history period? Like,
these moments, I don't know,

01:08:26.796 --> 01:08:30.646
musically, I don't understand how you create
them 'cause it might be bigger than musical.

01:08:30.656 --> 01:08:34.436
It might be cultural, all... a bunch of
different elements, and plus, it's him

01:08:34.556 --> 01:08:37.956
filled with ... Like, I've seen live
performances. He has, like, a headset. He

01:08:38.036 --> 01:08:42.026
does something. He's like a
telemarketer or something. Like,

01:08:42.056 --> 01:08:47.976
his whole vibe and look to him, he
doesn't look like a rockstar, but he is.

01:08:47.996 --> 01:08:51.696
- Those are hooks when you think about it,
right? It's like, it's as much of a hook

01:08:51.876 --> 01:08:55.476
as any, as the chorus of
the song or any song. That

01:08:55.556 --> 01:08:59.236
drum thing is something that people
wait for, and they air drum to it.

01:08:59.276 --> 01:09:02.556
Everybody air drums to
it, and it is a hook, and

01:09:03.236 --> 01:09:07.156
those are hard to create. Those are ...
Those moments are really hard to create,

01:09:07.176 --> 01:09:09.656
and usually they're done by accident.

01:09:09.716 --> 01:09:13.526
- Yes, it's hard. If you chase
it, you're not gonna get it.

01:09:13.536 --> 01:09:19.216
In your conversation with
Sting, he said something about

01:09:20.156 --> 01:09:27.046
how modern music is simpler, more minimalistic,
and, "The bridge is gone," I think-

01:09:27.156 --> 01:09:33.956
... he said. And he said he thought
that, "The bridge is therapy."

01:09:34.016 --> 01:09:37.696
It's, like, a chance for you to
reflect, I guess, on the verse-

01:09:37.705 --> 01:09:39.396
... before the chorus comes in.

01:09:39.406 --> 01:09:39.976
- That's right.

01:09:40.016 --> 01:09:43.826
- It changed my view of the bridge, I suppose,
is the therapeutic nature of it, at

01:09:43.856 --> 01:09:48.196
least lyrically. You think he's onto
something? The value of the bridge?

01:09:48.276 --> 01:09:52.056
- The bridge is a place, I think,
where you can kind of change

01:09:52.096 --> 01:09:55.196
the frame of reference of a song.

01:09:55.276 --> 01:09:56.896
- You could probably do anything, I guess.

01:09:56.976 --> 01:10:04.716
- Lennon used to... He would have
some kind of biting lyrics, like

01:10:04.726 --> 01:10:08.286
"We Can Work It Out." So McCartney
writes the, you know, "Try to see it my

01:10:08.376 --> 01:10:12.076
way. Do I have to keep on going until I can't
go on?" And then, but the bridge is very

01:10:12.176 --> 01:10:16.056
Lennon. "Life is very short, and there's
no time. For fussing and fighting, my

01:10:16.076 --> 01:10:20.046
friend. I have always thought that it's
a crime, so I'll ask you once again."

01:10:20.056 --> 01:10:23.645
I mean, it's very, you know, very
Lennon-esque. This is... That was really

01:10:23.645 --> 01:10:29.916
a... kind of a real collaboration
between the two of those.

01:10:29.956 --> 01:10:33.096
- This is where different
parts of the band can clash-

01:10:33.116 --> 01:10:36.925
... in interesting ways. I mean, the
Beatles are the epitome of that. Such ...

01:10:36.956 --> 01:10:42.736
Like, each individual Beatle is a
great talent in their own right.

01:10:42.816 --> 01:10:46.636
How were the Beatles able to
create some of the greatest

01:10:46.676 --> 01:10:50.796
songs of all time all before
they turned 30 years old?

01:10:51.116 --> 01:10:55.936
- I have never been able to figure
that out, but I have a theory

01:10:56.056 --> 01:10:58.316
that- ... because PA-

01:10:58.396 --> 01:10:59.196
- I have a theory.

01:10:59.216 --> 01:11:03.136
- Because PA systems were so bad back
then- ... and the Beatles ... People

01:11:03.376 --> 01:11:06.696
screamed so loudly that the
Beatles thought, "Okay. We

01:11:06.736 --> 01:11:10.576
don't, we don't need... We can't tour
anymore 'cause we can't even hear ourselves,

01:11:10.876 --> 01:11:14.356
so we're just gonna be a
studio band." And maybe

01:11:14.455 --> 01:11:18.386
because of... We have all these
great late Beatles records, they're

01:11:18.436 --> 01:11:24.616
from 1966 on, just because
they had bad PA systems.

01:11:24.676 --> 01:11:28.806
And they had no monitors. You
know, they're in Shea Stadium.

01:11:28.806 --> 01:11:32.186
People are screaming so loudly they can't hear
themselves. They're like, "Okay, forget this.

01:11:32.216 --> 01:11:36.116
We can't tour. We'll just make studio records,"
so that's what they did, and in that one

01:11:36.196 --> 01:11:42.196
year, like, from August 6th, 1965,
they put out Help. Then in December

01:11:42.436 --> 01:11:46.816
3rd, they put out Rubber
Soul, of '65. Then August

01:11:48.576 --> 01:11:52.076
5th, they put out Revolver. So within 365

01:11:52.156 --> 01:11:55.276
days, they put out three
14, I think, 14-song

01:11:55.345 --> 01:11:59.166
records. So they wrote and recorded three

01:11:59.216 --> 01:12:04.666
incredibly important records. They were
in the studio. It's like working out.

01:12:04.666 --> 01:12:08.276
They're practicing their
craft every day, writing

01:12:08.336 --> 01:12:11.546
songs, trying to outdo the other ones, and

01:12:12.356 --> 01:12:16.656
so you had the perfect thing
of four supremely talented

01:12:17.676 --> 01:12:21.316
musicians, songwriters,
singers, and then the best

01:12:21.336 --> 01:12:25.176
producer you could possibly
have, George Martin,

01:12:25.196 --> 01:12:29.136
and it was just a perfect
storm. I think that when

01:12:29.256 --> 01:12:33.196
I would talk to friends that would just
play in local clubs, and they'd play

01:12:33.276 --> 01:12:36.726
four-hour sets five nights a
week, and they never lost their

01:12:36.816 --> 01:12:40.316
voices because they're always
working those muscles.

01:12:40.356 --> 01:12:44.345
And same with the Beatles. They were
always in the studio singing every single

01:12:44.476 --> 01:12:51.656
day, doing takes, and I think that
that was part of it, at least.

01:12:51.676 --> 01:12:55.396
- But you also have this theory- that

01:12:56.316 --> 01:13:00.080
you know, that the greatest
productivity that musicians have is

01:13:00.200 --> 01:13:04.160
before they turn 30. The
greatest, sort of, creative

01:13:04.260 --> 01:13:09.540
genius that can come out of the human
mind musically is before the age of 30.

01:13:09.560 --> 01:13:12.220
- Well, I think it's the same
in mathematics, as well.

01:13:12.230 --> 01:13:16.680
You have this fluid intelligence
versus crystallized intelligence.

01:13:16.700 --> 01:13:19.920
Fluid intelligence up until you're
about, you know, in your late 20s,

01:13:19.960 --> 01:13:23.820
30 years old, and then crystallized,
so you're using... The crystallized is

01:13:23.940 --> 01:13:31.380
you're using your life experience to write
things, so you'll find that composers:

01:13:31.420 --> 01:13:35.360
Bach, Beethoven, Mozart wrote
their most important works at

01:13:35.400 --> 01:13:39.170
the end of their lives. Beethoven, the late
string quartets, the Ninth Symphony, things like

01:13:39.260 --> 01:13:43.130
that. So, they have a whole lifetime of
experience that lead up to this, and

01:13:43.140 --> 01:13:47.100
there's not... They're not improvising,
but things for improvising, writing pop

01:13:47.180 --> 01:13:54.900
songs, and that... I think when your mind
is really most active and your brain

01:13:54.980 --> 01:14:01.590
processing speed is at its pinnacle,
that... This is just my theory-

01:14:01.590 --> 01:14:05.360
... that people can come up with
those kind of ideas. Same with

01:14:05.400 --> 01:14:09.120
improvising. I think that most
jazz improvisers, not all, but

01:14:09.240 --> 01:14:13.720
most, do their best improvising
before the age of 30.

01:14:13.800 --> 01:14:15.100
- Creating something new.

01:14:15.160 --> 01:14:15.550
- Yes.

01:14:15.740 --> 01:14:19.980
- Truly novel, that requires youth.

01:14:20.840 --> 01:14:24.470
It's just a theory though, but it seems
to apply. What do you think about the

01:14:25.000 --> 01:14:28.720
27 Club? A bunch of the
music greats died at 27.

01:14:28.760 --> 01:14:33.820
Hendrix, Brian Jones, Jim Morrison,
Janis Joplin, Amy Winehouse.

01:14:33.860 --> 01:14:34.700
- Kurt Cobain.

01:14:34.740 --> 01:14:41.610
- Kurt Cobain, of course. A big part of
music history is linked to drug history.

01:14:43.560 --> 01:14:48.940
LSD, coke, heroin, weed.

01:14:48.980 --> 01:14:49.820
- Smoking.

01:14:49.920 --> 01:14:50.640
- Smoking.

01:14:50.880 --> 01:14:54.000
- I think about this a lot. If you
go back and you watch videos, The

01:14:54.080 --> 01:14:58.620
Beatles, any of their movies,
they're smoking all the time.

01:14:58.630 --> 01:15:02.580
The Get Back documentary, they're
smoking constantly. Go watch any of the

01:15:02.640 --> 01:15:06.429
MTV Unplugged, Nirvana, Kurt
Cobain is smoking every

01:15:06.560 --> 01:15:10.120
second that he's not playing,
he's smoking. Every singer

01:15:10.240 --> 01:15:14.100
smoked. Every musician
smoked. Nowadays, I asked

01:15:14.160 --> 01:15:16.890
my son, Dylan, "Dylan, does anybody
smoke" at his high school. He's like-

01:15:16.920 --> 01:15:19.880
..."Smoke? Nobody smokes." He's,
he's... The- it was an absurd

01:15:19.980 --> 01:15:24.560
question. And that was part of culture.

01:15:24.600 --> 01:15:28.570
- It was for everybody. I mean, that was, that was
a big transformation over the past 20 years and

01:15:28.640 --> 01:15:34.280
just everybody stopped smoking. But I
don't think smoking has the kinda hard

01:15:34.400 --> 01:15:38.240
negative effect that we're talking
about. I mean, I almost would

01:15:38.320 --> 01:15:42.140
rather have them smoke than some of
the other hard drugs. Maybe smoking

01:15:42.180 --> 01:15:45.990
distracts them from the
hard... I mean, heroin and

01:15:46.100 --> 01:15:50.060
coke, I mean, those, those things
really, and alcohol, unfortunately-

01:15:50.640 --> 01:15:56.220
... can be easily abused, I think. It
seems like it's a... The, the life of a

01:15:56.280 --> 01:16:02.860
musician, this dopamine thing
of getting on stage and be

01:16:02.870 --> 01:16:06.680
it, being adored by tens of
thousands, hundreds of thousands of

01:16:06.720 --> 01:16:10.580
people, the high of that,
and then the comedown after

01:16:11.620 --> 01:16:15.520
is a really hard life, for just
even neurobiologically, of like,

01:16:15.580 --> 01:16:18.740
how do you deal with that? You
have to be able to control

01:16:19.800 --> 01:16:23.430
the rollercoaster of your mind, and
of course drugs will be a part of

01:16:23.480 --> 01:16:26.560
that. And you think everything
is allowed and everything is

01:16:26.620 --> 01:16:30.600
possible. And then there's
also culture, depending on who

01:16:30.640 --> 01:16:34.620
you hang out with, that certain
kinds of categories of drugs

01:16:34.640 --> 01:16:42.360
are good for your creativity. And so,
naturally, you start to abuse those drugs.

01:16:43.360 --> 01:16:46.840
I don't know. I think
the, I think it's really

01:16:46.900 --> 01:16:50.800
interesting the role that drugs have played
in the, in the history of music. They have

01:16:51.200 --> 01:16:59.010
certainly been extremely destructive, but
they have also certainly been productive

01:16:59.080 --> 01:17:02.680
muses, inspirations for
some of these folks.

01:17:02.760 --> 01:17:06.460
- Oh, absolutely. Now, would we

01:17:06.500 --> 01:17:13.180
want to, you know, advocate people doing
things like that to boost their creativity?

01:17:13.340 --> 01:17:13.440
- No.

01:17:13.480 --> 01:17:19.560
- Well, I wouldn't, but just like smoking,
which I think improved people's voices-

01:17:21.320 --> 01:17:23.510
... I mean really, the raspiness of it-

01:17:23.560 --> 01:17:27.280
... this is the reason that
the, that so many of these,

01:17:27.300 --> 01:17:29.980
virtually every famous singer-

01:17:30.760 --> 01:17:37.260
... no matter what genre of music,
jazz, soul, rock, they all smoked.

01:17:37.320 --> 01:17:37.380
- Yeah, yeah.

01:17:37.400 --> 01:17:38.239
- Nat King Cole.

01:17:38.860 --> 01:17:40.080
- Miles Davis too?

01:17:40.120 --> 01:17:42.310
- Miles smoked, everybody smoked.
Miles did... Well, Miles

01:17:43.260 --> 01:17:44.640
was a heroin addict too. I mean-

01:17:44.700 --> 01:17:45.300
- Yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:17:45.310 --> 01:17:46.880
- ... so many jazz musicians.

01:17:46.940 --> 01:17:49.940
- Well, Miles had a sound to him.
You're right. I mean, smoking

01:17:50.020 --> 01:17:56.360
must, must play a gigantic role to that,
adding some complexity to the voice.

01:17:56.420 --> 01:17:56.940
- Yes.

01:17:56.980 --> 01:17:58.370
- Yeah, some richness to the voice.

01:17:58.400 --> 01:18:02.790
- Nat King Cole, he smoked, I think, four
packs a day. He died of lung cancer.

01:18:03.900 --> 01:18:07.720
Lotta heavy smokers though, as singers.

01:18:07.740 --> 01:18:11.650
Frank Sinatra, heavy smoker. McCartney
was a heavy smoker. Lennon, all

01:18:11.740 --> 01:18:13.160
those guys smoked.

01:18:13.220 --> 01:18:17.140
- Yeah, it's hard to know, chicken or the egg.
But I certainly wouldn't recommend doing

01:18:17.200 --> 01:18:22.360
drugs as a way to get better at music.

01:18:24.180 --> 01:18:28.080
But, you know, it does seem to
go hand-in-hand. And some of it

01:18:28.160 --> 01:18:31.660
has to do with the period, with
the time period, with the place,

01:18:32.040 --> 01:18:35.680
'cause sometimes it's part of the culture.
The drug is like you're saying, smoking.

01:18:35.760 --> 01:18:39.280
If you were smoking now, that's gonna
be a very different experience than

01:18:39.360 --> 01:18:42.760
smoking 10 years ago, 20 years
ago, 50 years ago. There's a

01:18:42.780 --> 01:18:46.530
different vibe. So,
sometimes the drug is a deep

01:18:47.160 --> 01:18:50.920
integrated part of the culture
versus an actual chemical

01:18:50.960 --> 01:18:54.590
substance. The '60s, right?
They're... I don't know. They were on

01:18:54.660 --> 01:18:56.020
everything in the '60s.

01:18:56.060 --> 01:19:04.160
- Yeah.... I mean, it has to account
for something, Lex, you know?

01:19:04.260 --> 01:19:08.160
- Uh, on the songwriting front, you
mentioned a story about Elton John

01:19:08.220 --> 01:19:12.100
recording. So he's one of the
legendary songwriters. But

01:19:12.160 --> 01:19:16.680
yeah. You've met him, and you know
something about the process of his, um-

01:19:17.000 --> 01:19:20.620
- Yeah, 'cause he was recording
in a studio in Atlanta that I

01:19:20.690 --> 01:19:24.610
was working with a band that I was producing.
And he was in, I was in Studio B, he was

01:19:24.640 --> 01:19:28.570
in Studio A. And this
band that I was working

01:19:28.580 --> 01:19:32.519
with, they were called Jump, Little Children. And
so, he had his assistant come in and ask, "Hey, is

01:19:32.560 --> 01:19:35.230
this... Are you guys Jump, Little Children?"
"Yeah, yeah, yeah." And then all of a

01:19:35.340 --> 01:19:39.300
sudden, I couldn't see out into the
live room. Elton walked into the

01:19:39.460 --> 01:19:43.300
thing, and we were getting ready to track, and
I'm, I'm pressing the button. "Yo, where are you

01:19:43.340 --> 01:19:47.080
guys? What's up? I thought we were gonna start
this." And no one's responding. I can hear

01:19:47.140 --> 01:19:50.800
talking, it's like, "What, what is going on? Where
are they?" Then all of a sudden they come back in the

01:19:50.880 --> 01:19:53.940
studio and they were stunned.
I said, "Where were you guys?"

01:19:54.600 --> 01:19:58.440
"Elton John just walked into our session.
And he said he's a big fan. He said to

01:19:58.480 --> 01:20:01.430
come over when we're done and,
and hang out in Studio A."

01:20:01.460 --> 01:20:05.380
So, so we did, and he was there
with Bernie Taupin, and they

01:20:05.420 --> 01:20:09.280
were working on a song. And he, we talked there
for, for an hour, and he was talking about

01:20:10.180 --> 01:20:14.000
recording two records a year, and then they'd
go on tour, and they'd write and record the

01:20:14.140 --> 01:20:16.880
whole record in two weeks.
So Bernie would give him

01:20:16.980 --> 01:20:20.560
lyrics. Elton would go out and spend 15

01:20:20.600 --> 01:20:24.540
minutes writing all the melody.
He'd look at his lyrics, and he was

01:20:24.580 --> 01:20:28.040
doing that that day. Bernie was there, and
they had a lyric sheet up on the piano.

01:20:28.800 --> 01:20:32.580
And Elton would go on, and they'd just... "Okay,
just record this." And Elton would sit there

01:20:32.640 --> 01:20:38.080
and, and play and come up with the
song- ... in 15 minutes or so.

01:20:38.180 --> 01:20:38.620
- Yeah, that's crazy.

01:20:38.640 --> 01:20:42.160
- There's a great version of, I think,
Tiny Dancer, where Elton is coming

01:20:42.220 --> 01:20:45.980
up with it on, it's on YouTube.
And he's just coming up with the

01:20:46.000 --> 01:20:49.740
music right there. And then the band, "Okay,
here's how it goes." And they record it right

01:20:49.820 --> 01:20:55.200
then. Then move onto the next song. I see
this. I mean, it's really incredible.

01:20:55.240 --> 01:20:59.220
That's it. Yeah. True. There's one there that
I've sort of done the other day with Tiny

01:20:59.280 --> 01:21:02.940
Dancer, which is about Bernie's
girlfriend. So I just sort

01:21:02.980 --> 01:21:06.680
of ran it through and then put two
verses together, then a mid-like, then a

01:21:06.720 --> 01:21:09.989
chorus, and then back to the sort of
verse sort of thing. It's, it's a very...

01:21:10.020 --> 01:21:13.560
It happens very quickly. It sounds long,
but it's sort of, it sort of starts

01:21:13.620 --> 01:21:31.260
off- &lt;&lt; Blue jean baby, LA lady, seamstress
for the band. Pirates man, pretty

01:21:31.380 --> 01:21:35.430
eye, you marry &gt;&gt;

01:21:35.480 --> 01:21:35.989
- Okay.

01:21:36.000 --> 01:21:38.260
- I mean, it's really amazing that he just-

01:21:38.269 --> 01:21:39.920
- Yeah. He's looking at just the lyrics.

01:21:39.940 --> 01:21:43.740
- Yeah, and it's one of the, he's one of
the very few people that has the lyrics

01:21:43.900 --> 01:21:49.360
first and writes the music to it,
which to me is far more difficult.

01:21:49.600 --> 01:21:53.480
99% of songwriters write the
music first, and then they

01:21:53.500 --> 01:21:58.170
put the melody and lyrics to
the finished backing track.

01:21:58.180 --> 01:22:03.960
- And maybe they write, like, lyrics, they
write, like, Nonsense words kind of-

01:22:04.000 --> 01:22:04.010
- Yes

01:22:04.010 --> 01:22:07.920
- ... thing. And then they figure out
from there. Yeah, that's... I mean, I

01:22:07.960 --> 01:22:11.020
don't know what skill that
is exactly, but that's

01:22:11.060 --> 01:22:15.520
incredible. I mean, in that
process he makes it his own.

01:22:15.560 --> 01:22:16.880
- Yes.

01:22:16.920 --> 01:22:23.000
- Okay. You had an amazing interview with
Kirk Hammett. I'm a huge Metallica fan.

01:22:23.060 --> 01:22:24.720
- Same here.

01:22:25.900 --> 01:22:28.980
- Uh, there is a lot of interesting
stuff that came out of that, from that

01:22:29.020 --> 01:22:33.660
conversation. One is the distinction
between heavy metal and hard rock.

01:22:34.180 --> 01:22:34.190
- Yes.

01:22:34.200 --> 01:22:37.440
- Which is very interesting. Of course,
Metallica went through their own

01:22:37.540 --> 01:22:42.760
evolution. They had many periods. I
mean, they've been around 40 years.

01:22:43.280 --> 01:22:45.420
- Over 40 years, yeah. Crazy.

01:22:45.440 --> 01:22:49.280
- The other thing is the downpicking,
which was interesting, which

01:22:49.380 --> 01:22:52.140
is creating that really distinct sound.

01:22:52.200 --> 01:22:55.460
- James and Kirk's, the down, the

01:22:55.620 --> 01:22:59.420
downpicking, I used to be able to do
that. I just can't do that anymore. It

01:22:59.460 --> 01:23:00.900
hurts my thumb-

01:23:00.960 --> 01:23:04.880
... to, to do it. I think honestly, I thought a
lot about it. It's like, why does it, why is it so

01:23:04.920 --> 01:23:09.610
painful? Why is it so hard? It's from
swiping with your thumb on phones.

01:23:09.640 --> 01:23:13.410
And I think it affects that basal joint
there, and, I'm sorry- No, I'm serious.

01:23:13.410 --> 01:23:14.600
- I love your theories.

01:23:14.610 --> 01:23:18.239
- Well, I think that that's actually right, 'cause I'm
thinking like, "Why does that hurt so much to do that?

01:23:18.299 --> 01:23:22.000
All the downstrokes and stuff." It's gotta be
something. It's like, yeah, it's from, from

01:23:22.080 --> 01:23:23.600
swiping with the phone.

01:23:23.680 --> 01:23:28.390
- The other thing that came through is
that he's an improviser at heart.

01:23:28.400 --> 01:23:32.180
And that, I think clashes with this
kind of rigid structure that metal is.

01:23:32.900 --> 01:23:36.840
So there's a real soulful, melodic
aspect to him. And he gave a

01:23:36.880 --> 01:23:40.640
lot of props to James Hetfield
for just being a great

01:23:40.720 --> 01:23:45.200
composer, being a great musician
and writer of riffs, of rhythm.

01:23:45.260 --> 01:23:48.800
- The improvisation part of it you don't
think of 'cause they've, they, 'cause you

01:23:49.320 --> 01:23:53.020
have the finished songs that you
listen to. But those songs are

01:23:53.060 --> 01:23:58.020
born out of improvisations, of
jams, of little fragments of ideas.

01:23:58.040 --> 01:24:03.980
And then they craft them
into these masterpieces.

01:24:04.040 --> 01:24:07.840
- Also, you mentioned that... This
is weird that I didn't know, that

01:24:07.880 --> 01:24:10.600
Hendrix was, used different
gauges of strings.

01:24:10.680 --> 01:24:13.230
- Yeah, he was the one that
talked about that, wasn't he?

01:24:13.240 --> 01:24:16.580
Yeah, that was really interesting. See,
these are the things that I like to

01:24:16.620 --> 01:24:20.180
learn from these interviews with these

01:24:20.220 --> 01:24:24.050
people. I was like, "What? Why
have I never heard of that?"

01:24:24.240 --> 01:24:25.820
- It's like, it's one of
the ways you can find

01:24:26.820 --> 01:24:30.800
uniqueness of sound, is by trying different
things that are not... I mean, I guess

01:24:30.960 --> 01:24:32.560
Apple was really good at this, right?

01:24:32.760 --> 01:24:36.600
Like, completely breaking out of what
you're supposed to do, the ways you're

01:24:36.640 --> 01:24:40.360
supposed to do them, and doing it
completely differently. You often ask

01:24:40.460 --> 01:24:45.920
musicians what their perfect song is. First
of all, that's an interesting question.

01:24:45.940 --> 01:24:47.460
- What is a perfect song?

01:24:47.560 --> 01:24:52.200
- Like, one surprise is, Hans Zimmer
said God Only Knows by the Beach Boys.

01:24:52.260 --> 01:24:55.780
- I was surprised by that too, but I thought it
was like, "Yeah, okay, that's a perfect song for

01:24:55.880 --> 01:24:59.040
sure." The first interview I ever
did was with Peter Frampton in

01:24:59.080 --> 01:25:02.830
2018, and I asked him in
that interview, "What's the

01:25:02.920 --> 01:25:06.780
perfect song?" And he said A Whiter
Shade of Pale. And I was like, "Ooh,

01:25:06.820 --> 01:25:10.304
that's a great song."
And I then I thought,

01:25:10.764 --> 01:25:14.544
"I'm gonna ask that to people, just to see
what they..." Now people are prepared if I ask

01:25:14.584 --> 01:25:14.784
that.

01:25:14.824 --> 01:25:18.174
- But it's like, they're willing
to go out on a limb and say it.

01:25:18.224 --> 01:25:21.784
Like, if you ask me, I don't even
know. I guess you just say it,

01:25:21.844 --> 01:25:24.844
whatever, right? Like, what would
I even say? What's a perfect

01:25:24.904 --> 01:25:29.604
song? Yeah, I would go...
See, I feel the pressure.

01:25:29.614 --> 01:25:30.224
- Right?

01:25:30.264 --> 01:25:36.304
- Because the problem is, the reality is,
it changes day by day, like minute by

01:25:36.404 --> 01:25:45.684
minute. I... Yeah, I would probably,
I'm sorry, but I would have to go Mark

01:25:45.704 --> 01:25:48.274
Knopfler. And I would probably go...

01:25:49.264 --> 01:25:52.944
Is it, is it really cheesy to say
the obvious thing? I would go

01:25:53.004 --> 01:25:58.333
Sultans of Swing. Even though like I'm
tempted to say Europa, but then like...

01:25:58.364 --> 01:26:00.604
- Sultans of Swing hits on so many levels-

01:26:00.614 --> 01:26:06.804
... 'cause it's got a great melody, great
lyrics, and then multiple great guitar

01:26:06.944 --> 01:26:11.844
solos. And has such a unique sound
to it. The other thing is that it

01:26:11.904 --> 01:26:15.224
sounds very different from other Dire
Straits songs. I mean, this is like early-

01:26:15.234 --> 01:26:18.804
... Dire Straits Strat tone. And then you
think of like Money for Nothing is a Les

01:26:18.924 --> 01:26:24.244
Paul, and it's a totally different
kind of vibe than him playing it on

01:26:24.304 --> 01:26:26.484
Sultans of Swing. But that song's amazing.

01:26:26.524 --> 01:26:31.864
- Plus it, it's about music. So it's
like there's a, there's a meta

01:26:32.664 --> 01:26:36.364
aspect to it. But then there's also like, we're
talking about this guitar stuff, but Leonard

01:26:36.404 --> 01:26:40.284
Cohen, Hallelujah. I mean, Leonard
Cohen in general. Like these

01:26:40.344 --> 01:26:43.644
songwriters, they go
super simple on guitar.

01:26:43.704 --> 01:26:50.104
And there, it's just what's that called?
Singer-songwriter type. Uh, I told you off

01:26:50.144 --> 01:26:56.744
my one of my, maybe the
music guest that's a

01:26:56.784 --> 01:27:00.664
dream guest is Tom Waits.
I've wanted to talk to

01:27:00.744 --> 01:27:05.534
Tom Waits for a very long time, and I've
gone through different periods of...

01:27:07.444 --> 01:27:11.384
You've met me at a point in my life where
I've given up on it a little bit. And I

01:27:11.394 --> 01:27:11.794
was trying-

01:27:11.804 --> 01:27:13.324
- That's when it's gonna happen. That's-

01:27:13.424 --> 01:27:13.744
- Okay.

01:27:13.824 --> 01:27:16.444
- Once you give up on it, it's gonna happen.

01:27:16.524 --> 01:27:19.904
- Yeah. Yeah.

01:27:19.923 --> 01:27:22.524
- Why Tom Waits won't be on your podcast.

01:27:23.124 --> 01:27:27.074
- Exactly. Exactly, dude. This is,
this is my, this is my moment.

01:27:27.074 --> 01:27:31.444
- Tom, come, come here. Let's
do it. I wanna see it.

01:27:31.504 --> 01:27:35.424
- I'm such a fan of, like the Zappa

01:27:35.464 --> 01:27:39.404
artistry on the musical
front, which Tom Waits has,

01:27:39.424 --> 01:27:43.344
but I'm a sucker for great
lyrics. Lyrics to me

01:27:43.364 --> 01:27:47.204
is such a big part of
great songs. And, and he's

01:27:47.244 --> 01:27:51.184
another example. He has a song
called Martha. It's about

01:27:51.464 --> 01:27:55.224
a love story that didn't work out,
and it's an older man calling

01:27:55.684 --> 01:27:59.304
the woman that he was in love
with, and basically reminiscing

01:27:59.384 --> 01:28:03.324
about like, you know, thinking about
like, "What would've happened if

01:28:03.344 --> 01:28:07.184
it worked out?" That kinda thing.
And then, you know, I loved that

01:28:07.244 --> 01:28:11.194
song for a long time, and you know

01:28:11.224 --> 01:28:14.484
at some point I found out that he
wrote that when he was in his early

01:28:14.724 --> 01:28:18.404
20s. And you realize, it's similar
with the Beatles, like- ... these

01:28:18.444 --> 01:28:21.894
guys somehow were able to
capture the human condition

01:28:22.684 --> 01:28:28.884
so masterfully, and they're kids. This,
I don't get it. I don't understand it.

01:28:29.044 --> 01:28:31.624
- I can't speak for Tom
Waits, but in the Beatles

01:28:32.584 --> 01:28:36.564
case, they went to Hamburg, they
spent time on their own, they played

01:28:36.624 --> 01:28:39.524
cover gigs that were eight
hours long, and they lived-

01:28:40.024 --> 01:28:40.684
- Yeah, they've lived

01:28:40.824 --> 01:28:45.424
- ... they lived life. It's not
like, not like kids today.

01:28:46.364 --> 01:28:53.604
- Now you're on a porch. You also had an
amazing interview with Billy Corgan, of

01:28:53.684 --> 01:28:59.094
Smashing Pumpkins. Uh, he is definitively
one of my favorite musicians.

01:28:59.104 --> 01:28:59.884
- I love Billy.

01:28:59.944 --> 01:29:03.624
- You asked him an interesting question
about how he creates this melancholy

01:29:03.684 --> 01:29:07.344
feeling that permeates a lot
of his songs, and he jokingly

01:29:07.504 --> 01:29:13.324
said that the secret is all about
the seventh and the ninth. Um,

01:29:14.664 --> 01:29:18.064
so like, musically, chord-wise, what do
you think about that? You think he's onto

01:29:18.104 --> 01:29:18.804
something?

01:29:18.884 --> 01:29:20.924
- He's talking a little music theory there.

01:29:21.264 --> 01:29:25.184
Seventh and ninth over the chord that he's playing.
So if you're playing a C chord, he's singing

01:29:25.224 --> 01:29:29.134
a B, would be the seventh, D would be
the ninth. And he does use a lot of

01:29:29.164 --> 01:29:33.034
those notes. But almost all these
people that we're talking...

01:29:33.064 --> 01:29:36.944
No, all these people that we're talking
about use these notes, and this is why

01:29:37.024 --> 01:29:40.644
their songs... When I interviewed
Sting, I called them surprise

01:29:40.704 --> 01:29:43.084
tones, and Sting's like, "I
like the way you use the word

01:29:43.124 --> 01:29:47.114
"surprise." Notes that are outside

01:29:47.144 --> 01:29:51.124
the chord that are dissonant with the chords
that they're playing, but then that creates

01:29:51.164 --> 01:29:54.584
emotion. Dissonance equals emotion. And

01:29:55.204 --> 01:29:59.044
that's what I like. I want
music to be... to depress me.

01:29:59.084 --> 01:30:02.744
- Yeah. What is that? I don't know. They,
the, but melancholy, and I think you

01:30:02.784 --> 01:30:06.694
articulate it in areas, it's not actually
that depressing. There's something

01:30:06.704 --> 01:30:08.284
about that melancholy feeling

01:30:09.584 --> 01:30:15.584
that is somehow the other side of the coin
of happiness. It's a kind of longing.

01:30:16.464 --> 01:30:20.304
Or there's a hopefulness to it. That aloneness that
you feel. I mean, that's actually like one of the

01:30:20.364 --> 01:30:24.124
intimate connections you have
with music, is when you're alone.

01:30:24.164 --> 01:30:28.144
There's, I think there's a social way of
listening to music when maybe a concert and

01:30:28.184 --> 01:30:32.164
so on, but there's this, there's
nothing like you're alone in a car

01:30:32.924 --> 01:30:36.404
driving, listening to,
like, whatever it is, Bruce

01:30:36.464 --> 01:30:39.954
Springsteen. Well, I think
Louis CK has a bit about

01:30:39.954 --> 01:30:43.884
that. And was it Bruce Springsteen?
But he's, sometimes he has to pull

01:30:43.964 --> 01:30:47.844
over to the side of the road and just
weep, or something like this. It's just

01:30:47.884 --> 01:30:51.324
the, there's something about that.
Sometimes a song just connects with you.

01:30:51.344 --> 01:30:55.304
And I don't know, nothing like a
melancholy song could do that.

01:30:55.344 --> 01:30:59.254
It... You think about, like,

01:30:59.304 --> 01:31:03.134
maybe things you regret or how life
could've worked out. And sometimes it's not

01:31:03.164 --> 01:31:06.984
even about, like... It's not
even real. It just connects

01:31:07.044 --> 01:31:10.744
something to the, in the soul.
The uneasiness that we all

01:31:10.804 --> 01:31:14.384
feel. Maybe the loneliness we all feel
that underpins so much of the human

01:31:14.424 --> 01:31:16.864
condition, and it just connects with
that. I don't know what that is.

01:31:16.904 --> 01:31:20.704
- There's a Kurt Cobain lyric.
It was on the In Utero record,

01:31:20.764 --> 01:31:24.544
from the song Frances Farmer.
The chorus part is, "I miss the

01:31:24.584 --> 01:31:31.648
comfort of being sad." And I was like,
"Yes." I miss the comfort in being

01:31:31.768 --> 01:31:35.708
sad&gt;&gt; I was like, "Yeah,
that's it right there."

01:31:35.768 --> 01:31:39.308
- In terms of love songs, I
somehow I find powerful

01:31:39.868 --> 01:31:44.548
that kind of desperation. So like I've
always connected with Pearl Jam's Black.

01:31:44.628 --> 01:31:46.288
- Oh, amazing.

01:31:46.308 --> 01:31:50.188
- Like that line is... A friend of mine
was going through a breakup, so I was

01:31:50.228 --> 01:31:54.188
listening and he, he's the one that
introduced me to Pearl Jam during that whole

01:31:54.288 --> 01:32:02.968
period when Pearl Jam was huge
with Ten. That line is "Someday-"

01:32:02.978 --> 01:32:06.768
- "Someday you'll have a beautiful
life. You know, someday you'll be a

01:32:06.848 --> 01:32:15.308
star in somebody else's sky. Why, why,
why can't it be mine?" Oh my God, that—

01:32:15.548 --> 01:32:19.108
... blows me away. That's an amazing line.

01:32:19.128 --> 01:32:19.958
- Well, yeah, I mean-

01:32:19.968 --> 01:32:22.348
- The delivery is incredible on it too.

01:32:22.358 --> 01:32:24.488
- Yeah. Eddie Vedder, one of the
great frontmen of all time.

01:32:24.528 --> 01:32:24.828
- Yes.

01:32:24.848 --> 01:32:28.518
- And that whole period, that
whole moment in history

01:32:28.888 --> 01:32:32.748
of Kurt Cobain and Eddie
Vedder that captured... That

01:32:32.788 --> 01:32:36.148
was the '90s. That was
one side of the '90s that

01:32:36.288 --> 01:32:40.728
just... This singular moment in history.
Who, who do you think are the great

01:32:41.728 --> 01:32:44.468
frontmen in history of music?

01:32:44.488 --> 01:32:47.127
- Freddie Mercury, Robert Plant.

01:32:47.188 --> 01:32:48.868
- Freddie Mercury number one, probably.

01:32:48.878 --> 01:32:50.128
- Steven Tyler.

01:32:50.168 --> 01:32:50.968
- Jim Morrison.

01:32:51.008 --> 01:32:51.688
- Jim Morrison?

01:32:52.288 --> 01:32:52.298
- ...

01:32:52.348 --> 01:32:56.008
- Yeah. Roger Daltrey. Um-

01:32:56.048 --> 01:33:00.728
- Well, we have to say, I have to
say, we have to say James Hetfield.

01:33:00.748 --> 01:33:01.648
- James Hetfield?

01:33:01.708 --> 01:33:05.588
- I mean, there's nothing... I mean,
I have to talk to you about this.

01:33:05.648 --> 01:33:09.268
I have... I mean, it's just the greatest,
I think the greatest concert of all

01:33:09.308 --> 01:33:13.268
time. This is their historic performance

01:33:13.308 --> 01:33:17.038
in Moscow in September
of '91. This is shortly

01:33:17.048 --> 01:33:23.048
before the Soviet Union collapsed. Plus,
we should mention AC/DC and Pantera-

01:33:23.108 --> 01:33:27.088
... were there too. And about
1.6 million people were

01:33:27.148 --> 01:33:30.328
there. Now, by the way,
there's like some kind of

01:33:30.388 --> 01:33:33.728
reporting that there was
a half a million people,

01:33:33.908 --> 01:33:37.858
500,000 people. There's somewhere I've
seen statements like that. That's a

01:33:37.868 --> 01:33:43.788
ridiculously inaccurate statement. So it's
a free concert, so any official counts

01:33:45.048 --> 01:33:49.018
don't count. It's, it's
definitely over a million.

01:33:49.028 --> 01:33:52.888
It's, it's very likely to be 1.5,
1.6 million people. And this

01:33:52.928 --> 01:33:56.608
moment in history that I think
they channeled, it's like

01:33:56.648 --> 01:34:00.568
whenever great music, the... Metallica
was firing on all cylinders at the

01:34:00.588 --> 01:34:04.568
very top of their game, and they meet this
moment in history and this place in history.

01:34:04.588 --> 01:34:07.648
There was a defining
part of the 20th century

01:34:07.728 --> 01:34:12.608
collapsing, and you have
these people who are

01:34:13.788 --> 01:34:17.708
for a moment through music, are
able to escape the fear, the anger

01:34:17.768 --> 01:34:21.268
they feel, the... all of it.
There was also a political,

01:34:21.348 --> 01:34:23.428
social, cultural moment meeting

01:34:24.368 --> 01:34:28.118
the musical moment, and the set
list, I was just... I was li-

01:34:28.328 --> 01:34:32.128
I listened to it several times over
the past few days, just taking myself

01:34:32.188 --> 01:34:36.068
back into that moment in time.
Listen to this set list. Enter

01:34:36.148 --> 01:34:39.508
Sandman, Creeping Death,
Harvester of Sorrow, Fade to

01:34:39.608 --> 01:34:43.148
Black, Sad but True, Master
of Puppets, Seek and

01:34:43.208 --> 01:34:50.168
Destroy, For Whom the Bell Tolls, One,
and Whiplash. Look at that. How is that-

01:34:50.228 --> 01:34:52.717
- That's- just- That's my kind of set

01:34:52.717 --> 01:34:53.608
- ... get the fuck out of here.

01:34:53.668 --> 01:34:53.798
- That's-

01:34:53.798 --> 01:34:54.818
- This is amazing. This is-

01:34:54.818 --> 01:34:56.928
- That's my kind of set right there.

01:34:57.008 --> 01:34:59.628
- I don't know if you can think of
anything that could beat that.

01:34:59.688 --> 01:35:03.068
- I think that the guys in the band would say that,
too. That was... I mean, they were really at

01:35:03.108 --> 01:35:07.528
their, at their peak. The Black
Album had just come out then, and

01:35:08.608 --> 01:35:12.678
that must have been so, so exciting.

01:35:12.708 --> 01:35:16.418
- I mean, Woodstock was big. There's
certain moments in time that really,

01:35:16.448 --> 01:35:21.368
really meet the moment. Are you
a fan of live, live like big?

01:35:21.488 --> 01:35:24.328
- I used to be, but at this point-

01:35:24.628 --> 01:35:31.348
... I can't you know... I'd much
rather see people play in small clubs-

01:35:31.388 --> 01:35:37.648
... and, or go to the... I'd like to listen
in the studio. Go to the studio, even.

01:35:37.708 --> 01:35:41.608
- I generally almost entirely agree with
you. I just think that there's these

01:35:41.628 --> 01:35:43.178
historic moments, but you don't know-

01:35:43.178 --> 01:35:46.308
... which are gonna be which,
but you're making the concert

01:35:46.467 --> 01:35:53.648
free, it's just all of it, you
get plus Pantera and AC/DC. The

01:35:53.728 --> 01:35:57.638
other, which actually is a
legitimate thing you mentioned, is

01:35:57.708 --> 01:35:59.728
as one of the greatest
concerts of all time

01:36:00.608 --> 01:36:04.428
is Beethoven's world premiere
of Ninth Symphony. You know, I

01:36:04.468 --> 01:36:08.188
didn't really know the personal
side of Beethoven until I

01:36:08.268 --> 01:36:12.778
saw this movie called Immortal Beloved.
It's an excellent movie with, uh-

01:36:12.788 --> 01:36:13.488
- Gary Oldman

01:36:13.688 --> 01:36:17.648
- ... Gary Oldman. Just a really... it's a
masterful celebration of Beethoven in an

01:36:17.748 --> 01:36:21.268
interesting kind of way through the
perspective of a love letter that he's

01:36:21.288 --> 01:36:24.978
written. But then I realized like... and
this is early, this is many, many...

01:36:24.988 --> 01:36:28.428
this is a couple decades ago now,
that, you know, he went deaf

01:36:29.108 --> 01:36:32.728
before he even started writing the Ninth
Symphony, which is why they consider it to

01:36:32.768 --> 01:36:36.728
be one of the greatest compositions
of all time, the greatest symphonies

01:36:36.768 --> 01:36:40.568
of all time. He went deaf,
couldn't hear anything

01:36:41.328 --> 01:36:45.228
before he even started writing it.
And so there's that famous story

01:36:45.288 --> 01:36:49.108
of him in that world premiere of

01:36:49.168 --> 01:36:52.917
having to be turned around because he
can't hear people applauding, so he has

01:36:52.948 --> 01:36:56.888
to be turned around to see that
people are actually clapping. I mean,

01:36:56.908 --> 01:36:59.488
there's just this whole
tragic element. Plus,

01:37:00.548 --> 01:37:04.088
the meaning of the
symphony that ends in this

01:37:04.148 --> 01:37:07.968
beautiful Ode to Joy, the
symphony itself is a kind

01:37:08.048 --> 01:37:12.968
of... It starts with the
chaos and conflict and ends

01:37:13.888 --> 01:37:18.968
with this celebration of peace and

01:37:20.488 --> 01:37:26.828
brotherly unity and a- I guess a call
for that, a reaching for that, for

01:37:26.908 --> 01:37:30.688
that peace. And it's a... and there's a
tragic element to it, again, connected to

01:37:30.708 --> 01:37:33.868
history, which is it was
post Napoleonic Wars-

01:37:33.888 --> 01:37:37.808
... and before the American Civil
War. So like, you're in this, in this

01:37:37.928 --> 01:37:45.472
middle...... this respite from war,
calling for peace, not knowing that truly

01:37:45.552 --> 01:37:49.412
horrific wars are coming. So you have the American
Civil War, and you have the, of course, the two

01:37:49.452 --> 01:37:53.432
World Wars coming. So this,
all of it together, and the

01:37:53.492 --> 01:37:57.432
fact that he's conducting deaf, and
he wrote this whole thing deaf.

01:37:57.472 --> 01:38:01.172
I was reading a lot about his process,
and he just edits and edits and edits and

01:38:01.232 --> 01:38:07.532
edits. So the fact that he had to
edit in his head is just insane.

01:38:07.592 --> 01:38:11.531
- I mean, it— Beethoven was sick all the time too.
I mean, a lot of people were sick all the time.

01:38:11.552 --> 01:38:17.872
It was very common. What
would motivate you to write

01:38:19.372 --> 01:38:23.052
music, this beautiful music that
you can never actually hear

01:38:23.112 --> 01:38:29.572
except for in your head? Right? Like, why...
The amount of time it takes to write,

01:38:30.392 --> 01:38:34.212
to write a 35-minute,
40-minute piece, all the

01:38:34.272 --> 01:38:38.152
parts, you got to hear all the
orchestration in your head. You're editing,

01:38:38.172 --> 01:38:42.792
you're doing all these things. Where do
you get the motivation when you can't

01:38:44.052 --> 01:38:49.472
hear the actual finished work? One,
and people would say, "Well, he's

01:38:49.492 --> 01:38:53.352
hears in his head." But what
kind of enjoyment is it? You

01:38:53.412 --> 01:39:00.452
wanna hear the orchestra... I mean,
it's really profound that he was

01:39:00.492 --> 01:39:03.992
inspired to do this. There's a
thing called the Heiligenstadt

01:39:04.032 --> 01:39:07.952
Testament that he wrote. It was
a letter to his brothers in,

01:39:07.992 --> 01:39:11.292
from 1802. I think they found
it in his desk after Beethoven

01:39:11.412 --> 01:39:14.402
died, and he felt a sense of shame and

01:39:14.432 --> 01:39:18.362
humiliation because of his hearing
loss. And he said that he was

01:39:18.392 --> 01:39:24.712
afflicted with this thing where him
of all people, that someone standing

01:39:24.772 --> 01:39:28.692
next to him could hear a flute
that he could not hear, or

01:39:28.772 --> 01:39:32.712
a shepherd singing in the field
that... And he could not hear

01:39:32.752 --> 01:39:36.732
this. And, and of all the people,
why him? Where hearing played

01:39:36.772 --> 01:39:40.752
such an important part. Another
person that would have had

01:39:40.792 --> 01:39:44.212
to have had perfect pitch,
'cause you could never do this-

01:39:44.792 --> 01:39:48.611
... if you didn't have perfect pitch, which I think
all of these great composers, for the most part.

01:39:48.632 --> 01:39:52.412
Brahms didn't, from what I know, but
all the rest of them, for sure, had

01:39:52.452 --> 01:39:56.332
perfect pitch. So they could hear these
things in their head, and that's how

01:39:56.372 --> 01:39:57.452
they composed.

01:39:57.712 --> 01:40:02.532
- I mean, you love sound and music.

01:40:03.592 --> 01:40:07.812
What do you think it was like gradually
losing your hearing for Beethoven?

01:40:08.752 --> 01:40:16.472
- It must have been terrible. I
mean, I, just... Terrible. I mean,

01:40:16.532 --> 01:40:20.432
I've heard things where he would
have a stick in his mouth, and put

01:40:20.472 --> 01:40:23.072
it on the soundboard of the
piano, and you could feel the

01:40:23.092 --> 01:40:26.122
vibrations in his skull,
and things like that.

01:40:26.272 --> 01:40:27.772
- Yeah, desperately trying to-

01:40:27.812 --> 01:40:29.972
- Yeah. I just—

01:40:30.512 --> 01:40:33.672
- But also, there's, what is, what
is that, that he's able to write

01:40:35.772 --> 01:40:38.892
like one of the greatest
symphonies ever, while

01:40:38.901 --> 01:40:43.292
deaf? So there's something about that.
We mentioned darkness, but torment

01:40:44.172 --> 01:40:51.612
that he's going through. And ultimately,
Ode to Joy. Like, not a cynical thing—

01:40:51.772 --> 01:40:54.872
... but a call for the positive.

01:40:55.772 --> 01:41:04.072
- Yeah. Yeah. That's, that's— I've devoted
many, many hours thinking about that.

01:41:04.092 --> 01:41:08.882
- And plus, Napoleon broke his heart,
because he was a supporter of Napoleon-

01:41:08.882 --> 01:41:10.432
... because Napoleon was
supposed to represent

01:41:11.332 --> 01:41:15.312
the French Revolution, this, this
hopeful future of no more kings,

01:41:15.372 --> 01:41:18.992
no more monarchs, no more
authoritarian regimes. And

01:41:19.232 --> 01:41:22.672
Napoleon ended up becoming,
essentially, king.

01:41:22.712 --> 01:41:27.612
Uh, becoming an authoritarian.
And Beethoven, sort of

01:41:28.572 --> 01:41:32.202
famously was critical of that. Nevertheless,
I think maintained a fascination with

01:41:32.232 --> 01:41:35.852
Napoleon throughout his life.
But sort of a kind of more

01:41:36.132 --> 01:41:39.572
sophisticated, complex view
of human nature and human

01:41:39.612 --> 01:41:43.572
civilization. So becoming
more cynical. Like, seeing

01:41:44.432 --> 01:41:48.212
more clearly that the world
disappoints you, that dreams get

01:41:48.252 --> 01:41:56.112
shattered. And through that, is able to
still do this call for the hopeful future.

01:41:56.152 --> 01:42:00.132
All right, so okay. So Beethoven,
one of the greats, for

01:42:00.172 --> 01:42:03.992
sure. Like basically
everybody, I know how to

01:42:04.032 --> 01:42:07.832
play the first movement of Moonlight
Sonata, but I always avoided the third

01:42:07.892 --> 01:42:11.812
movement 'cause I was like,
"I'll never be good enough."

01:42:11.852 --> 01:42:13.982
Never, never, but I need to-

01:42:13.982 --> 01:42:14.992
- Never say never, Lex.

01:42:15.032 --> 01:42:18.952
- One of these days, maybe. You know
what would be great? If Tom Waits

01:42:19.072 --> 01:42:22.492
writes me an email that says,
"I only talk to people that can

01:42:22.532 --> 01:42:23.972
play-" "... the third movement."

01:42:23.982 --> 01:42:24.162
- Play the third movement.

01:42:24.192 --> 01:42:26.852
- That'd be, that'd be a dream come true.

01:42:26.892 --> 01:42:27.262
- There you go.

01:42:27.262 --> 01:42:28.202
- I'd be like, "For this-"

01:42:28.252 --> 01:42:29.022
- That's motivation.

01:42:29.022 --> 01:42:32.922
- "That's my dragon," or whatever you do.
You have to have a prince and rescue the

01:42:32.992 --> 01:42:36.392
princess. My dragon is the third
movement of Moonlight Sonata.

01:42:36.432 --> 01:42:42.302
Okay. You often highlight the importance of
Bach. In fact, so many of your guests...

01:42:42.332 --> 01:42:45.112
- Every famous songwriter is
influenced by Bach. They

01:42:45.232 --> 01:42:50.232
